00:02:50.880 --> 00:02:55.880
[Amit Varma]: Roshan, I invited you, of course, because of your really interesting data journalism

00:02:55.880 --> 00:02:58.520
[Amit Varma]: and your writing on politics and so on and so forth.

00:02:58.520 --> 00:03:03.400
[Amit Varma]: But after inviting you, I found out that when you were a student, you were also into politics

00:03:03.400 --> 00:03:05.440
[Amit Varma]: yourself and all of that.

00:03:05.440 --> 00:03:09.640
[Amit Varma]: So tell me a little bit about that, not just the political aspect of it, but you know,

00:03:09.640 --> 00:03:11.440
[Amit Varma]: what kind of person were you when you were young?

00:03:11.440 --> 00:03:12.440
[Amit Varma]: What interested you?

00:03:12.440 --> 00:03:14.280
[Amit Varma]: You know, where did you study?

00:03:14.280 --> 00:03:15.280
[Guest]: What did you study?

00:03:15.280 --> 00:03:22.000
[Guest]: Basically, I'm from Bihar and I, you know, which is the normal thing, at least it was

00:03:22.000 --> 00:03:25.760
[Guest]: in our generation then that you had to qualify the IITG and all that.

00:03:25.760 --> 00:03:32.040
[Guest]: And I studied sciences for my plus two and I was really very bad at it.

00:03:32.040 --> 00:03:36.720
[Guest]: But luckily, I took economics as a subject because you had to take a fifth subject, computer

00:03:36.720 --> 00:03:39.760
[Guest]: economics, and I thought I enjoyed it.

00:03:39.760 --> 00:03:44.800
[Guest]: So after I made a disaster of my plus two stint, I decided to come and pursue economics

00:03:44.800 --> 00:03:46.560
[Guest]: in Delhi University.

00:03:46.560 --> 00:03:49.720
[Guest]: And even then, I'd never given a lot of thought to it.

00:03:49.720 --> 00:03:55.120
[Guest]: I think as things evolved, I also and more than that, my teachers, a couple of whom happened

00:03:55.120 --> 00:03:59.520
[Guest]: to be from JNU, realized that, you know, looking at the qualitative economic picture was something,

00:03:59.520 --> 00:04:03.520
[Guest]: you know, I had an aptitude and encouraged me to take the JNU entrance exam.

00:04:03.520 --> 00:04:08.900
[Guest]: And no, I got through and no, as you know, the JNU economics course is radically different

00:04:08.900 --> 00:04:13.640
[Guest]: compared to what the other premier institutions in this country like Delhi School or IGA do.

00:04:13.640 --> 00:04:18.440
[Guest]: I'm not saying that the former is good or the latter is bad, but it is a more heterodox

00:04:18.440 --> 00:04:19.440
[Guest]: sort of a thing.

00:04:19.440 --> 00:04:21.880
[Amit Varma]: Tell me a little bit about how it's different.

00:04:21.880 --> 00:04:26.520
[Guest]: The crux of it, I think is, you know, a lot of people say that, you know, it's no more

00:04:26.520 --> 00:04:28.080
[Guest]: Marxian etc.

00:04:28.080 --> 00:04:31.120
[Guest]: But I think JNU, I don't know what it is now.

00:04:31.120 --> 00:04:36.640
[Guest]: But I think the basic focus was they somehow, you know, emphasize the Kaleski-Keynes framework

00:04:36.640 --> 00:04:40.320
[Guest]: and classical political economy was sort of emphasized upon.

00:04:40.320 --> 00:04:44.840
[Guest]: So rather than, you know, you start running econometrics and regression equations, etc.

00:04:44.840 --> 00:04:49.440
[Guest]: from day one, and you essentially go the job market way because a lot of analysts, you

00:04:49.440 --> 00:04:53.160
[Guest]: should remember that that was the boom period then before the crisis, you know, when I went

00:04:53.160 --> 00:04:58.520
[Guest]: to university and corporate jobs were really, I mean, coming at a very fast pace.

00:04:58.520 --> 00:05:03.000
[Guest]: So rather than just do that, I mean, JNU does that also a lot of people from JNU have excelled

00:05:03.000 --> 00:05:07.240
[Guest]: in those kinds of fields, it also allowed you to the opportunity to look at classical

00:05:07.240 --> 00:05:08.240
[Guest]: political economy.

00:05:08.240 --> 00:05:12.280
[Guest]: So we had courses like political economy of development, where you would see, you know,

00:05:12.280 --> 00:05:16.640
[Guest]: what kind of trajectory China take, the Korean-Japanese war, those sorts of things, the feudalism

00:05:16.640 --> 00:05:17.640
[Guest]: capitalism debate.

00:05:17.640 --> 00:05:19.920
[Guest]: I'm not that I remember all of those today.

00:05:19.920 --> 00:05:24.920
[Guest]: But it allowed you to, I mean, try and look at the larger economic pictures, if I could

00:05:24.920 --> 00:05:31.480
[Guest]: say and it also allowed me to sort of develop my own arguments, you know, we were not very

00:05:31.480 --> 00:05:35.400
[Guest]: good at it when we were young students, but at least try and get the larger picture develop

00:05:35.400 --> 00:05:39.560
[Guest]: arguments question basic assumptions behind arguments which are being made.

00:05:39.560 --> 00:05:45.360
[Guest]: A lot of comparative studies, you know, I joined my MA in economics in 2004.

00:05:45.360 --> 00:05:48.640
[Guest]: This was just a couple of years after the East Asian crisis had hit.

00:05:48.640 --> 00:05:51.840
[Guest]: And no three, four years before the larger global crisis hit.

00:05:51.840 --> 00:05:55.840
[Guest]: So those are very interesting times to be in the discipline, you know, even then there

00:05:55.840 --> 00:06:01.320
[Guest]: was a lot of charm for the corporate world and you know, mainstream economic theory,

00:06:01.320 --> 00:06:03.060
[Guest]: but it was an interesting period.

00:06:03.060 --> 00:06:09.480
[Guest]: And I think, you know, because ours was a department which had very eminent left leaning

00:06:09.480 --> 00:06:13.600
[Guest]: economists like Professor Prabhat Patnayak, Utsav Patnayak, Jyoti Ghosh.

00:06:13.600 --> 00:06:17.800
[Guest]: So they influenced a lot of our, to a very large degree, our worldview as well.

00:06:17.800 --> 00:06:21.200
[Guest]: And then, you know, because JNU is JNU, politics also happened.

00:06:21.200 --> 00:06:24.880
[Guest]: And you know, the economics department is always, it has historically been a stronghold

00:06:24.880 --> 00:06:31.400
[Guest]: of the SFI, so to say, the left leaning students, people like Sitaram, etc. are alumni.

00:06:31.400 --> 00:06:32.640
[Guest]: So it was a mix of the two.

00:06:32.640 --> 00:06:35.000
[Guest]: So the academic and the political sort of came together.

00:06:35.000 --> 00:06:36.440
[Guest]: That's the ideological aspect of it.

00:06:36.440 --> 00:06:41.960
[Guest]: But I also believe, you know, that I've been out of my home after my class 10th.

00:06:41.960 --> 00:06:45.080
[Guest]: So plus two, I did in different city where there were no hostels.

00:06:45.080 --> 00:06:50.160
[Guest]: So basically at a very young age, I was, we were friends running a flat, a kitchen, etc.

00:06:50.160 --> 00:06:51.800
[Guest]: And life is very difficult when you do that.

00:06:51.800 --> 00:06:56.600
[Guest]: So JNU was the first time I actually went to a hostel and life in JNU is as convenient

00:06:56.600 --> 00:06:58.520
[Guest]: as you can get for a student.

00:06:58.520 --> 00:07:02.020
[Guest]: Now that I look back at it, I also think that, you know, one can be critical that it does

00:07:02.020 --> 00:07:06.200
[Guest]: not make you do enough hard work, unless you are sort of self driven and motivated, you

00:07:06.200 --> 00:07:09.600
[Guest]: will get along easily in JNU, this is something I also did.

00:07:09.600 --> 00:07:15.160
[Guest]: But that also played an important part in shaping my worldview, because the left was

00:07:15.160 --> 00:07:20.040
[Guest]: a strong force in the union there and the history of student struggles, etc. in JNU.

00:07:20.040 --> 00:07:23.040
[Guest]: Today, all of it is looked down upon, unfortunately.

00:07:23.040 --> 00:07:28.160
[Guest]: But that was the second, I think, but also an essential aspect of it.

00:07:28.160 --> 00:07:33.080
[Amit Varma]: And was there a moment during all this or a phase during all this where it struck you

00:07:33.080 --> 00:07:38.080
[Amit Varma]: that economics is not just something in a book, it's not just a theoretical subject,

00:07:38.080 --> 00:07:42.680
[Amit Varma]: but it explains your world and it explains your world so viscerally that then it is a

00:07:42.680 --> 00:07:47.640
[Amit Varma]: natural step for you to want to get involved in politics, for example, and you know, all

00:07:47.640 --> 00:07:51.280
[Amit Varma]: of it becomes one congruous whole.

00:07:51.280 --> 00:07:53.880
[Guest]: That I believe has always been true.

00:07:53.880 --> 00:08:00.600
[Guest]: It's, it's, it's not for me to say, you know, for example, no great economic catastrophes,

00:08:00.600 --> 00:08:04.920
[Guest]: something like the Great Depression, I mean, I mean, it could not be arrested in time because

00:08:04.920 --> 00:08:08.240
[Guest]: people believed in the Say's law, you know, that supply will create its own demand, and

00:08:08.240 --> 00:08:09.480
[Guest]: therefore, there's no need to.

00:08:09.480 --> 00:08:13.640
[Guest]: Now, we know that Keynes had sort of, you know, pointed out those mistakes with the

00:08:13.640 --> 00:08:19.560
[Guest]: basic theoretical framework earlier, but it took a Second World War, it took a, you know,

00:08:19.560 --> 00:08:25.000
[Guest]: Soviet camp to sort of put that extra pressure to start that corrective mechanism after you

00:08:25.000 --> 00:08:28.880
[Guest]: know, the Second World War ended, the golden age of capitalism has been no aid, even if

00:08:28.880 --> 00:08:33.760
[Guest]: we look at, you know, for example, today, there's a lot of discussion about why India

00:08:33.760 --> 00:08:37.640
[Guest]: couldn't embark on that manufacturing success story like the Aryan Station countries, even

00:08:37.640 --> 00:08:43.600
[Guest]: China later, now, a lot of development economics today, even mainstream economies, I think

00:08:43.600 --> 00:08:48.560
[Guest]: the role of the fact that, you know, egalitarian land distribution was done even in these countries,

00:08:48.560 --> 00:08:52.840
[Guest]: you know, which after the Second World War went to the sort of the capitalist block,

00:08:52.840 --> 00:08:56.640
[Guest]: but you know, breaking up land monopoly played a crucial role in those things.

00:08:56.640 --> 00:09:01.280
[Guest]: So that way, definitely, if you look at the text, also, I think this ample evidence to

00:09:01.280 --> 00:09:06.200
[Guest]: suggest that economics plays a role and politics plays a role in determining the economic trajectory

00:09:06.200 --> 00:09:08.480
[Guest]: of societies, nations, etc.

00:09:08.480 --> 00:09:09.480
[Guest]: That's one.

00:09:09.480 --> 00:09:16.640
[Guest]: Now, let us come back to JNU again, now, JNU is a place where you pay even today, I think

00:09:16.640 --> 00:09:18.860
[Guest]: a few hundred rupees in fees.

00:09:18.860 --> 00:09:26.520
[Guest]: So it actually allows you to, you know, pursue things which you like without, you know, feeling,

00:09:26.520 --> 00:09:30.720
[Guest]: I would say burdened by the fact that you probably have to get out of the university

00:09:30.720 --> 00:09:32.560
[Guest]: and pay lakhs of rupees in student loans.

00:09:32.560 --> 00:09:37.040
[Guest]: So, you know, I do not exactly come from a very poor family, but you know, most middle

00:09:37.040 --> 00:09:41.380
[Guest]: class Indians, you know, like my socio economic background, could not have afforded this kind

00:09:41.380 --> 00:09:44.760
[Guest]: of study if they had to pay, say, student loans.

00:09:44.760 --> 00:09:48.200
[Guest]: So those kind of intellectual choices, which I was able to make earlier in my life, and

00:09:48.200 --> 00:09:52.240
[Guest]: know of which the professional reward I'm reaping today, you know, without, you know,

00:09:52.240 --> 00:09:57.280
[Guest]: having to have ever paid for that, you know, subsidised education, which I received, I

00:09:57.280 --> 00:10:01.160
[Guest]: think in a country like India, it still makes a lot of sense to at least have, you know,

00:10:01.160 --> 00:10:05.040
[Guest]: if not all some higher educational institutions, which allow people to do that, because if

00:10:05.040 --> 00:10:09.800
[Guest]: you if breaking even becomes the sole point of education, and this need not know just

00:10:09.800 --> 00:10:13.840
[Guest]: confine itself to economics, any other discipline, I think you'd end up with a very different

00:10:13.840 --> 00:10:15.720
[Amit Varma]: intellectual trajectory in any country or society.

00:10:15.720 --> 00:10:20.680
[Amit Varma]: In fact, I had I had coffee yesterday with a friend who's studying right now in JNU.

00:10:20.680 --> 00:10:23.800
[Amit Varma]: He's doing his postgraduate economics, shout out to Sanjit.

00:10:23.800 --> 00:10:26.440
[Amit Varma]: And he and the tuition fees are still pretty much as low.

00:10:26.440 --> 00:10:29.960
[Amit Varma]: In fact, he says he pays more for his hostel and for his tuition fees.

00:10:29.960 --> 00:10:32.760
[Amit Varma]: And that also sounded like a really small amount to me.

00:10:32.760 --> 00:10:37.600
[Amit Varma]: So what was politics like, like, you know, today, I think of you as one of the sharpest

00:10:37.600 --> 00:10:42.740
[Amit Varma]: minds in political journalism and in covering the political economy and so on.

00:10:42.740 --> 00:10:46.660
[Amit Varma]: And it's fascinating to me that you were also at one point a politician yourself.

00:10:46.660 --> 00:10:51.560
[Amit Varma]: Is there any sort of correlation between politics on a bigger scale and the kind of politics

00:10:51.560 --> 00:10:52.640
[Amit Varma]: on the smaller scale?

00:10:52.640 --> 00:10:55.440
[Amit Varma]: And what was politics on that smaller scale really like?

00:10:55.440 --> 00:10:59.520
[Guest]: I think it makes a lot of difference, you know, because I was never an active participant

00:10:59.520 --> 00:11:00.520
[Guest]: in it.

00:11:00.520 --> 00:11:04.320
[Guest]: But I've seen politics in Delhi University, now Delhi University, for example, I was looking

00:11:04.320 --> 00:11:09.560
[Guest]: at the papers yesterday, so some 70,000 students have taken admission in BA first year.

00:11:09.560 --> 00:11:15.560
[Guest]: So if you look at it, when the DUSU elections happen, you're probably talking about an electorate,

00:11:15.560 --> 00:11:16.560
[Amit Varma]: which is more than 2 lakh strong.

00:11:16.560 --> 00:11:21.880
[Guest]: We're recording on July 30, by the way, yeah, so you can't have any intellectual engagement

00:11:21.880 --> 00:11:22.880
[Guest]: with that kind of crowd.

00:11:22.880 --> 00:11:28.160
[Guest]: It is, you know, physically, humanly impossible to even know, think of doing it.

00:11:28.160 --> 00:11:31.160
[Guest]: Now, compared to this, JNU is the exact opposite.

00:11:31.160 --> 00:11:33.320
[Guest]: When we were students, we had around 4000 students.

00:11:33.320 --> 00:11:38.240
[Guest]: So politics essentially was a lot of room to room campaigns, going to students having,

00:11:38.240 --> 00:11:42.480
[Guest]: you know, discussing things ad nauseam with them, a lot of which, you know, the outside

00:11:42.480 --> 00:11:46.120
[Guest]: world would think is probably, you know, purely romanticism and doesn't have any bearing on

00:11:46.120 --> 00:11:47.120
[Guest]: the larger world.

00:11:47.120 --> 00:11:52.840
[Guest]: But even then, the crucial thing about JNU was your success or lack of success in politics

00:11:52.840 --> 00:11:56.880
[Guest]: actually dependent on your ability to a do hard work, because, you know, it takes a lot

00:11:56.880 --> 00:12:02.440
[Guest]: of your time, be your ability to sort of come up with arguments and counter arguments.

00:12:02.440 --> 00:12:05.280
[Guest]: And the ideological spectrum was very different.

00:12:05.280 --> 00:12:06.840
[Guest]: But this I think was the crux of the matter.

00:12:06.840 --> 00:12:11.400
[Guest]: And unlike a lot of, you know, what people believe, it actually had a material bearing

00:12:11.400 --> 00:12:12.400
[Guest]: on school.

00:12:12.400 --> 00:12:14.480
[Guest]: For example, when we were students, we fought agitations.

00:12:14.480 --> 00:12:18.440
[Guest]: So JNU, I don't know whether it's still the case, JNU used to, even though the fees etc

00:12:18.440 --> 00:12:22.000
[Guest]: were really low, it used to give scholarships to students who came whose family income was

00:12:22.000 --> 00:12:26.600
[Guest]: below a certain threshold, I think when we were students, it was 75,000 rupees per year.

00:12:26.600 --> 00:12:28.120
[Guest]: So this was only for BA, MA.

00:12:28.120 --> 00:12:33.320
[Guest]: Now the question, you know, which we found most difficult was, once you finished your

00:12:33.320 --> 00:12:38.120
[Guest]: MA, you got into an MPhil or a PhD program, now, technically, that's work research in

00:12:38.120 --> 00:12:41.280
[Guest]: any first world country, you paid a lot of money for that.

00:12:41.280 --> 00:12:45.080
[Guest]: In JNU, that was not the case, be India still doesn't have that kind of a developed sort

00:12:45.080 --> 00:12:48.560
[Guest]: of academic labor market where you could go out and earn your money.

00:12:48.560 --> 00:12:50.160
[Guest]: Those days projects are always still coming.

00:12:50.160 --> 00:12:53.200
[Guest]: So making ends meet was really a difficult thing to do.

00:12:53.200 --> 00:12:57.640
[Guest]: And even if you come from a relatively well off family or not so poor family, you can't

00:12:57.640 --> 00:13:01.320
[Guest]: ask your family for no sort of supporting yourself beyond post graduation.

00:13:01.320 --> 00:13:05.200
[Guest]: So we fought an agitation and Professor Thorat used to be the UGC chairman and some sort

00:13:05.200 --> 00:13:10.040
[Guest]: of a scholarship started, it was bare minimum to make ends meet 3000-5000 rupees.

00:13:10.040 --> 00:13:15.560
[Guest]: So politics was, you know, identifying what these material problems were trying to look

00:13:15.560 --> 00:13:20.640
[Guest]: for a constituency in JNU, which would sort of identify with these demands and support

00:13:20.640 --> 00:13:22.520
[Guest]: these demands.

00:13:22.520 --> 00:13:27.160
[Guest]: And then, you know, having the larger ideological debates at the same time, for example, JNU,

00:13:27.160 --> 00:13:31.160
[Guest]: so I joined JNU in four, now four is the year when the NDA one actually lost power.

00:13:31.160 --> 00:13:35.640
[Guest]: So, you know, May were the elections and I went to JNU in July and I believe, but before

00:13:35.640 --> 00:13:40.000
[Guest]: that, the five years JNU being JNU had problems with the first NDA regime as well.

00:13:40.000 --> 00:13:41.600
[Guest]: Those were problems of a very different nature.

00:13:41.600 --> 00:13:44.680
[Guest]: You know, there was Gujarat riots and all those things.

00:13:44.680 --> 00:13:49.200
[Guest]: But then politics qualitatively shifted, I would say for the 10 years under the UPA government,

00:13:49.200 --> 00:13:53.560
[Guest]: because the right wing challenge was not so much of a challenge, then it completely shifted

00:13:53.560 --> 00:13:58.120
[Guest]: to things such as more scholarships, more hostels, etc, on the one hand, and then, you

00:13:58.120 --> 00:14:02.560
[Guest]: know, issues such as say, the nuclear deal, you know, which is not it doesn't have a material

00:14:02.560 --> 00:14:07.680
[Guest]: impact on you, but nevertheless, given JNU's ideological leanings is a big debate, Shingur

00:14:07.680 --> 00:14:13.280
[Guest]: Nandigram was a watershed event in JNU, because CPM slash SFI, its student wing has always

00:14:13.280 --> 00:14:16.080
[Guest]: enjoyed an intellectual hegemony, so to say.

00:14:16.080 --> 00:14:22.480
[Guest]: But once the Shingur Nandigram thing happened, it really sort of gave a body blow to that

00:14:22.480 --> 00:14:23.480
[Guest]: ideological hegemony.

00:14:23.480 --> 00:14:30.200
[Guest]: So the 2007 elections were the first elections where the SFI lost all major posts.

00:14:30.200 --> 00:14:34.680
[Guest]: And this had only happened once after the TNMN elections.

00:14:34.680 --> 00:14:39.520
[Guest]: So JNU that way gives you a very rich political profile, I mean, and experience because you're

00:14:39.520 --> 00:14:42.400
[Guest]: dealing with, I mean, pretty much everything under the sun.

00:14:42.400 --> 00:14:48.060
[Guest]: But nevertheless, I mean, people who are voted are equally if not more likely to desert you

00:14:48.060 --> 00:14:51.000
[Guest]: on those ideological issues for more concrete issues.

00:14:51.000 --> 00:14:55.680
[Guest]: So that way, I think a lot of what you know, you know, the political arguments and I can

00:14:55.680 --> 00:14:59.000
[Guest]: make or the way I can think JNU has contributed a lot to that.

00:14:59.000 --> 00:15:02.400
[Amit Varma]: And what was the impetus behind your getting into politics to begin with?

00:15:02.400 --> 00:15:05.760
[Amit Varma]: Like, was it that, okay, these things need to be done, and someone's got to do them and

00:15:05.760 --> 00:15:07.760
[Guest]: I'm going to get into politics and get it done?

00:15:07.760 --> 00:15:09.720
[Guest]: Well, there was no political ambition.

00:15:09.720 --> 00:15:13.160
[Guest]: So when I joined SFI, I did not even know that it was a CPM student wing.

00:15:13.160 --> 00:15:19.800
[Guest]: I think the biggest question was, see, for joining any kind of politics, you have to

00:15:19.800 --> 00:15:23.560
[Guest]: have an instinct for social engagement that, you know, my world is not just me, but I want

00:15:23.560 --> 00:15:24.840
[Guest]: to engage with the larger world.

00:15:24.840 --> 00:15:30.480
[Guest]: But in my case, I think the most important thing was a sense of gratitude to what JNU

00:15:30.480 --> 00:15:33.560
[Guest]: offered to a student like me, because life was very easy.

00:15:33.560 --> 00:15:36.880
[Guest]: It was for the first time in my student life after having got out of my home, the comforts

00:15:36.880 --> 00:15:40.520
[Guest]: of my home, I actually did not have to worry about anything else but my studies.

00:15:40.520 --> 00:15:45.120
[Guest]: So it was this sense of gratitude, which, you know, sort of attracted me to JNU then

00:15:45.120 --> 00:15:47.480
[Guest]: continues to attract me to JNU even today.

00:15:47.480 --> 00:15:51.800
[Amit Varma]: Right, so in those years when you were sort of, you know, doing your MPhil, I think you

00:15:51.800 --> 00:15:52.800
[Guest]: did an MPhil.

00:15:52.800 --> 00:15:53.800
[Guest]: I finished my MPhil.

00:15:53.800 --> 00:15:54.800
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

00:15:54.800 --> 00:15:57.320
[Amit Varma]: So in those years that you did an MPhil, and you also stood for president of the JNU.

00:15:57.320 --> 00:15:58.320
[Guest]: I did.

00:15:58.320 --> 00:15:59.320
[Guest]: And those elections never happened.

00:15:59.320 --> 00:16:03.600
[Guest]: So JNU elections were stayed for the nonconformity to link the committee recommendations.

00:16:03.600 --> 00:16:07.000
[Guest]: So I was a presidential candidate who never contested that way.

00:16:07.000 --> 00:16:10.000
[Guest]: But I've been in the union and other smaller posts.

00:16:10.000 --> 00:16:12.760
[Amit Varma]: So what were your sort of aspirations in those days?

00:16:12.760 --> 00:16:15.120
[Amit Varma]: Like you told me, you don't always think you'll be a journalist.

00:16:15.120 --> 00:16:20.240
[Amit Varma]: What were your sort of aspirations like, and also, what were your interests like, like

00:16:20.240 --> 00:16:22.200
[Amit Varma]: your deep knowledge of data?

00:16:22.200 --> 00:16:25.000
[Amit Varma]: Is that something you started building up at that point in time?

00:16:25.000 --> 00:16:29.480
[Amit Varma]: What were your influences like, how was your, like, who are the thinkers who influenced

00:16:29.480 --> 00:16:30.480
[Amit Varma]: you?

00:16:30.480 --> 00:16:32.000
[Amit Varma]: What are the books you would recommend to my listeners, for example?

00:16:32.000 --> 00:16:38.600
[Guest]: There are two ways to look at it, the place where I come from in the country, higher education

00:16:38.600 --> 00:16:41.640
[Guest]: actually went down the drain in Bihar in the 70s itself.

00:16:41.640 --> 00:16:44.880
[Guest]: So there's been a large intellectual void, so to say.

00:16:44.880 --> 00:16:49.320
[Guest]: And education, because if you could afford it, you would get out of Bihar, it was as

00:16:49.320 --> 00:16:50.320
[Guest]: simple as that.

00:16:50.320 --> 00:16:53.760
[Guest]: Anybody who could afford it would not do his or her college or university education in

00:16:53.760 --> 00:16:58.320
[Guest]: Bihar, unless you wanted to make a complete disaster out of your academic career or professional

00:16:58.320 --> 00:16:59.320
[Guest]: career.

00:16:59.320 --> 00:17:04.200
[Guest]: So as long as I was at home, education meant a degree of professional success.

00:17:04.200 --> 00:17:08.120
[Guest]: You get good marks in class 10, then you go to class 12, you either get into a medical

00:17:08.120 --> 00:17:10.800
[Guest]: school or an engineering school or things like that.

00:17:10.800 --> 00:17:13.960
[Guest]: Then when I was in BA, it was many things put together.

00:17:13.960 --> 00:17:17.600
[Guest]: Some of us wanted to prepare for the civil services, somebody, you know, management CAT

00:17:17.600 --> 00:17:22.280
[Guest]: was a big thing, then some of us wanted to do, you know, places like JNU, D school and

00:17:22.280 --> 00:17:25.200
[Guest]: probably go outside for GRE, etc.

00:17:25.200 --> 00:17:28.880
[Guest]: When I came to JNU, I came with a very open mind, you know, none of these were foreclosed

00:17:28.880 --> 00:17:29.880
[Guest]: options.

00:17:29.880 --> 00:17:31.320
[Guest]: I'd never made up my mind.

00:17:31.320 --> 00:17:37.280
[Guest]: Once the option started, and I saw that I had an interest in political economy, I gradually,

00:17:37.280 --> 00:17:41.040
[Guest]: politics also played a role in it, I gradually made up my mind that I'll finish a PhD in

00:17:41.040 --> 00:17:44.320
[Guest]: JNU, probably get a teaching job, as simple as that.

00:17:44.320 --> 00:17:46.640
[Guest]: Now that never happened, because I never finished my PhD.

00:17:46.640 --> 00:17:53.280
[Guest]: But the data bit, I think, again, JNU has a lot of role to play, because, you know,

00:17:53.280 --> 00:17:57.600
[Guest]: the basic courses which we did, so even know things such as political economy of development,

00:17:57.600 --> 00:17:58.600
[Guest]: etc.

00:17:58.600 --> 00:18:02.680
[Guest]: So for example, you know, my professor who eventually became my supervisor, Utsa Pattanaik,

00:18:02.680 --> 00:18:06.600
[Guest]: she actually says that it is Lenin who discovered the Lorenz curve.

00:18:06.600 --> 00:18:09.840
[Guest]: So Lenin, you know, he has this famous book called Development of Capitalism in Russia,

00:18:09.840 --> 00:18:11.840
[Guest]: in which he plotted those curves.

00:18:11.840 --> 00:18:17.160
[Guest]: So we were taught that unless your facts sort of back it up, you can't make an argument

00:18:17.160 --> 00:18:18.440
[Guest]: that's not done.

00:18:18.440 --> 00:18:24.240
[Guest]: Because no matter how ideologically persuasive it sounds, or no matter how much in agreement

00:18:24.240 --> 00:18:28.240
[Guest]: everybody is in it, as far as research is concerned, you have to have some substantive

00:18:28.240 --> 00:18:29.240
[Guest]: proof.

00:18:29.240 --> 00:18:30.240
[Guest]: So data work is sacrosanct.

00:18:30.240 --> 00:18:33.480
[Guest]: So I'm somebody who never did field for my research, but a lot of my research was based

00:18:33.480 --> 00:18:37.640
[Guest]: on secondary NSS data, I worked on the public distribution system, etc.

00:18:37.640 --> 00:18:41.880
[Guest]: So it was then that I realized that, you know, you have to have some factual thing, a lot

00:18:41.880 --> 00:18:46.880
[Guest]: of my time as a political activist, so the only thing, you know, comparable to what a

00:18:46.880 --> 00:18:50.800
[Guest]: journalist does, which I did in JNU was because JNU has this culture of distributing dinner

00:18:50.800 --> 00:18:51.800
[Guest]: pamphlets.

00:18:51.800 --> 00:18:53.960
[Guest]: So on your mess table, every day, there are pamphlets.

00:18:53.960 --> 00:18:57.720
[Guest]: And because I happen to be in the SFI, anybody who leads an organization has to write those

00:18:57.720 --> 00:18:58.720
[Guest]: pamphlets.

00:18:58.720 --> 00:19:01.040
[Guest]: So four o'clock, we would decide, you know, what to write on.

00:19:01.040 --> 00:19:03.880
[Guest]: And within an hour, you had to produce this 600 word copy.

00:19:03.880 --> 00:19:08.840
[Guest]: And that is the closest thing I did, a journalist does, you know, as far as JNU is concerned.

00:19:08.840 --> 00:19:12.960
[Guest]: But again, then, you say, if you look at the budget, etc, the one way was to go about it

00:19:12.960 --> 00:19:17.040
[Guest]: was to know just throw adjectives, and everybody would agree even then, but the other way was

00:19:17.040 --> 00:19:18.040
[Guest]: to actually look at data.

00:19:18.040 --> 00:19:21.360
[Guest]: So for example, if the budget has come, what has happened to say educational allotment,

00:19:21.360 --> 00:19:23.920
[Guest]: this scholarship, that scholarship, etc.

00:19:23.920 --> 00:19:26.500
[Guest]: Even when you were negotiating with the administration.

00:19:26.500 --> 00:19:31.880
[Guest]: So the fact that data was a useful skill set to have, you know, academically as well as

00:19:31.880 --> 00:19:35.280
[Guest]: not to be in a political argument is something JNU taught me.

00:19:35.280 --> 00:19:39.200
[Guest]: And that always stayed with me, because, you know, I was never very good at, you know,

00:19:39.200 --> 00:19:42.320
[Guest]: other quantitative stats, such as game theory, or microeconomics, etc.

00:19:42.320 --> 00:19:46.800
[Guest]: So that was the natural sort of leaning I acquired, and I used to like it also.

00:19:46.800 --> 00:19:51.400
[Guest]: So, you know, for a brief while between journalism and JNU, I was in research there also, I was

00:19:51.400 --> 00:19:57.120
[Guest]: looking at food security, I mean, how the Americans support their farm, agriculture,

00:19:57.120 --> 00:19:58.360
[Guest]: etc.

00:19:58.360 --> 00:20:03.360
[Guest]: And every day, I would realize that if you add the numbers, your case become really strong.

00:20:03.360 --> 00:20:05.320
[Guest]: So that is how data happened to me.

00:20:05.320 --> 00:20:10.000
[Guest]: Once again, I think, part of my academic political training, whatever one might call it.

00:20:10.000 --> 00:20:14.240
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, it strikes me that while data is objective, the numbers are what they are,

00:20:14.240 --> 00:20:15.560
[Amit Varma]: the facts are what they are.

00:20:15.560 --> 00:20:20.060
[Amit Varma]: And you mentioned before this, when we were having lunch before the recording, that the

00:20:20.060 --> 00:20:24.160
[Amit Varma]: useful thing about data is that it makes you question your prior beliefs and your biases,

00:20:24.160 --> 00:20:25.840
[Amit Varma]: you have to back it up with data.

00:20:25.840 --> 00:20:30.360
[Amit Varma]: But isn't it also the case that there is so much of data that you can, you know, use data

00:20:30.360 --> 00:20:34.520
[Amit Varma]: to almost support any conclusion, you can cherry pick data, you can, you know, torture

00:20:34.520 --> 00:20:37.200
[Guest]: data till it confesses the truth, as someone famously said.

00:20:37.200 --> 00:20:38.200
[Guest]: No, exactly.

00:20:38.200 --> 00:20:43.080
[Guest]: This is something I try and bring out on my own work as well now as a journalist.

00:20:43.080 --> 00:20:47.000
[Guest]: For example, if we were to look at, say, the unemployment rate in India, latest figures

00:20:47.000 --> 00:20:48.840
[Guest]: show that some 6.1%.

00:20:48.840 --> 00:20:52.640
[Guest]: Even when it was not that high, if you were to compare, say, unemployment rate in a country

00:20:52.640 --> 00:20:56.920
[Guest]: like India with a with an OECD country, I mean, the rates there would probably be much

00:20:56.920 --> 00:20:57.920
[Guest]: higher.

00:20:57.920 --> 00:21:02.120
[Guest]: Because, you know, being unemployed in a first world country and being unemployed in a country

00:21:02.120 --> 00:21:03.920
[Guest]: like India are completely different things.

00:21:03.920 --> 00:21:09.040
[Guest]: I mean, an NREGA worker is technically considered employed in India.

00:21:09.040 --> 00:21:13.560
[Guest]: That would not be the case in, say, Sweden, or even in the United States, for most of

00:21:13.560 --> 00:21:15.840
[Guest]: the people in the US at least.

00:21:15.840 --> 00:21:19.720
[Guest]: So you of course, have to know the context in which the data is being, I mean, given

00:21:19.720 --> 00:21:20.720
[Guest]: to you.

00:21:20.720 --> 00:21:24.920
[Guest]: And which is why, you know, rather than one data point, you have to have multiple data

00:21:24.920 --> 00:21:25.920
[Guest]: points.

00:21:25.920 --> 00:21:30.800
[Guest]: And, and, you know, you have to know what, what exactly is the data point you're looking

00:21:30.800 --> 00:21:33.280
[Guest]: at, you know.

00:21:33.280 --> 00:21:38.320
[Guest]: For example, in demonetization, a lot of people said that, you know, because these cash hoards

00:21:38.320 --> 00:21:41.600
[Guest]: would be purchased, so we will get rid of black money.

00:21:41.600 --> 00:21:45.080
[Guest]: Somebody who has done his or her basic economics would know that that is not the case.

00:21:45.080 --> 00:21:47.320
[Guest]: Now there are stocks and there are flows.

00:21:47.320 --> 00:21:49.360
[Guest]: Black money, we know is a flow variable.

00:21:49.360 --> 00:21:53.880
[Guest]: So if I had 1000 rupees of black money sitting in my pocket, if it were to get extinguished

00:21:53.880 --> 00:21:58.320
[Guest]: today, in six months from now, I probably had 2000 rupees of black money in my pocket.

00:21:58.320 --> 00:22:04.200
[Guest]: So I think it is extremely important, especially in journalism, because and this is something,

00:22:04.200 --> 00:22:10.560
[Guest]: once again, I value a lot from my initial days, as long as I was in school, probably

00:22:10.560 --> 00:22:16.080
[Guest]: the only nonfiction I've ever read in my life are newspapers, because you know, places in

00:22:16.080 --> 00:22:20.440
[Guest]: Bihar, even today, I do not think a very strong library culture, etc.

00:22:20.440 --> 00:22:24.920
[Guest]: So all my knowledge about the world was either from TV or newspapers.

00:22:24.920 --> 00:22:25.920
[Guest]: That's it.

00:22:25.920 --> 00:22:29.320
[Guest]: I mean, people take extremely seriously what is written in newspapers.

00:22:29.320 --> 00:22:32.600
[Guest]: I mean, I would not say that for television today, but at least even today, newspapers,

00:22:32.600 --> 00:22:35.360
[Amit Varma]: if people read them, they take it very seriously.

00:22:35.360 --> 00:22:38.080
[Amit Varma]: And in your case, it was like English newspapers or Hindi also?

00:22:38.080 --> 00:22:41.960
[Guest]: I was not very comfortable reading English newspapers until school, but I would read

00:22:41.960 --> 00:22:42.960
[Guest]: Hindi papers.

00:22:42.960 --> 00:22:44.880
[Guest]: It was more a language problem rather than anything else.

00:22:44.880 --> 00:22:48.800
[Guest]: The moment I got comfortable with English, I started reading English newspapers.

00:22:48.800 --> 00:22:55.280
[Guest]: But so I think it is our duty to sort of, you know, do our own hard work and get our

00:22:55.280 --> 00:22:59.680
[Guest]: own concepts right while we are dealing with data, that I consider is extremely important.

00:22:59.680 --> 00:23:04.320
[Guest]: And not all data, you know, should be presented in the form of jargon, etc.

00:23:04.320 --> 00:23:09.200
[Guest]: Basic things such as and I think it is more important to use data to ask questions rather

00:23:09.200 --> 00:23:10.200
[Guest]: than answer them.

00:23:10.200 --> 00:23:14.840
[Guest]: Now, for example, we know that, you know, everybody knows that four quarters GDP growth

00:23:14.840 --> 00:23:16.240
[Guest]: has been declining.

00:23:16.240 --> 00:23:17.480
[Guest]: That's there.

00:23:17.480 --> 00:23:19.240
[Guest]: So what does one make out of it?

00:23:19.240 --> 00:23:20.600
[Guest]: Who does it impact?

00:23:20.600 --> 00:23:22.600
[Guest]: Which sectors is it impacting?

00:23:22.600 --> 00:23:26.960
[Guest]: What should we you know, a lot of people on the left, for example, used to say that, you

00:23:26.960 --> 00:23:30.920
[Guest]: know, this entire obsession with trickle down growth theory that, you know, growth should

00:23:30.920 --> 00:23:33.800
[Guest]: be the be all and end all of economic policy is not good.

00:23:33.800 --> 00:23:34.800
[Guest]: This is neoliberal.

00:23:34.800 --> 00:23:35.800
[Guest]: All right, well taken.

00:23:35.800 --> 00:23:39.760
[Guest]: But today, when the GDP declines, I mean, how do the same people go and criticize the

00:23:39.760 --> 00:23:43.560
[Guest]: government for growth, then you have to have a larger theory or an explanation of who's

00:23:43.560 --> 00:23:47.920
[Guest]: getting impacted by this deceleration in growth, how much I think as journalists, we need to

00:23:47.920 --> 00:23:52.360
[Guest]: sort of answer those questions, and also ask those questions, because there are a lot of

00:23:52.360 --> 00:23:56.440
[Guest]: people about today's world economy, polity, these are the two things I am comfortable

00:23:56.440 --> 00:24:01.520
[Guest]: with, I'm sure applies to a lot of other things as well, where we do not know the answers.

00:24:01.520 --> 00:24:06.680
[Guest]: But I think at least an attempt has to be made, especially, you know, from the profession

00:24:06.680 --> 00:24:10.120
[Guest]: I work in journalism to be able to ask those questions.

00:24:10.120 --> 00:24:15.080
[Amit Varma]: And have there been moments where, for example, you've gone into looking at a subject with

00:24:15.080 --> 00:24:20.480
[Amit Varma]: certain prior assumptions, and found and changed your mind after looking at the data completely?

00:24:20.480 --> 00:24:23.600
[Amit Varma]: Like, is there something memorable like that, which you remember?

00:24:23.600 --> 00:24:28.800
[Guest]: Well, there's one puzzle, which I know, I think we need some more data points.

00:24:28.800 --> 00:24:32.400
[Guest]: For example, this entire demonetization thing which happened now the government said that

00:24:32.400 --> 00:24:37.720
[Guest]: it'll aid, you know, tax collection, etc, because the tax base will widen up and all

00:24:37.720 --> 00:24:38.720
[Guest]: that.

00:24:38.720 --> 00:24:42.800
[Guest]: Now, this budget, there's been a shortfall, but the income tax numbers, you know, have

00:24:42.800 --> 00:24:45.880
[Guest]: still been growing quite, quite robustly.

00:24:45.880 --> 00:24:51.080
[Guest]: Even after demonetization, corporate tax is not growing, GST is not growing.

00:24:51.080 --> 00:24:54.080
[Guest]: So how much of it is because of demonetization?

00:24:54.080 --> 00:24:58.360
[Guest]: How much of it is because of normal things is something no, because no, I've criticized

00:24:58.360 --> 00:25:02.440
[Guest]: demonetization a lot in my academic works, and I'm not the only one who's criticized it,

00:25:02.440 --> 00:25:03.960
[Guest]: a lot of people have done that.

00:25:03.960 --> 00:25:09.280
[Guest]: But the data doesn't allow me to still make a substantive final argument that this is

00:25:09.280 --> 00:25:12.320
[Guest]: what we know about say demonetization's impact on income tax collections.

00:25:12.320 --> 00:25:16.880
[Guest]: Now, we know that those tall claims are probably will never be made, but has there been some

00:25:16.880 --> 00:25:17.880
[Guest]: impact?

00:25:17.880 --> 00:25:18.880
[Guest]: Has there not been an impact?

00:25:18.880 --> 00:25:20.640
[Guest]: I would still like to wait for some time.

00:25:20.640 --> 00:25:22.560
[Guest]: So this is where I think data becomes useful.

00:25:22.560 --> 00:25:27.240
[Guest]: It prevents you from sort of, you know, grandstanding about your own ideas or your own prejudices

00:25:27.240 --> 00:25:28.360
[Guest]: if one could use the word.

00:25:28.360 --> 00:25:31.840
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, and I've also ranted and raved about demon and I have a bunch of episodes on it,

00:25:31.840 --> 00:25:32.960
[Amit Varma]: which are linked from the show notes.

00:25:32.960 --> 00:25:39.400
[Amit Varma]: But then, you know, that brings me to the question of what do you do when data sources

00:25:39.400 --> 00:25:43.680
[Amit Varma]: aren't adequate, or when they are not adequately trustworthy?

00:25:43.680 --> 00:25:47.120
[Amit Varma]: For example, demon, it would be fair to assume that a significant part of the impact was

00:25:47.120 --> 00:25:49.200
[Amit Varma]: on the informal sector.

00:25:49.200 --> 00:25:53.340
[Amit Varma]: And we don't have direct data from the informal sector, one has to make sort of assumptions

00:25:53.340 --> 00:25:56.040
[Amit Varma]: based on other proxies.

00:25:56.040 --> 00:26:00.500
[Amit Varma]: You know, and even apart from the informal sector, where data is a problem, there's also

00:26:00.500 --> 00:26:05.000
[Amit Varma]: the growing issue of how much of data which comes from the government is reliable anymore.

00:26:05.000 --> 00:26:09.720
[Amit Varma]: Like I had an episode recently on the GDP with economist Rajeshwari Sengupta, and who's

00:26:09.720 --> 00:26:12.200
[Amit Varma]: in sort of an expert on it.

00:26:12.200 --> 00:26:16.680
[Amit Varma]: And it left me alarmed because at the end of it, the feeling I got was that GDP has

00:26:16.680 --> 00:26:21.920
[Amit Varma]: now become less of an economic measure and more of a political rhetorical tool.

00:26:21.920 --> 00:26:26.000
[Amit Varma]: And if you can't trust those kinds of figures that the government puts out, and if you don't

00:26:26.000 --> 00:26:32.360
[Amit Varma]: have independent means of getting that kind of data yourself, then what is one to do?

00:26:32.360 --> 00:26:38.080
[Amit Varma]: I mean, do you then rely on some kind of jugaad with the data that is available and that you

00:26:38.080 --> 00:26:39.080
[Amit Varma]: know is reliable?

00:26:39.080 --> 00:26:40.560
[Guest]: Or how do you navigate that?

00:26:40.560 --> 00:26:44.880
[Guest]: As far as the particular question about GDP is concerned, I think and you know, it is

00:26:44.880 --> 00:26:48.840
[Guest]: unfortunate that that is the case, unless the government, like you said, decides to,

00:26:48.840 --> 00:26:54.040
[Guest]: you know, sort of make it open to at least an independent panel of economists, experts,

00:26:54.040 --> 00:26:55.880
[Guest]: we would never know.

00:26:55.880 --> 00:27:00.080
[Guest]: That's sad for a country like us, we are not some banana republic, we are a big country,

00:27:00.080 --> 00:27:05.080
[Guest]: in terms of population in terms of our economic size in the world.

00:27:05.080 --> 00:27:09.520
[Guest]: But then I think it becomes and, you know, these debates, you know, are so politically

00:27:09.520 --> 00:27:14.500
[Guest]: colored now that it is impossible to sort of, you know, pinpoint as to who's being objective

00:27:14.500 --> 00:27:18.600
[Guest]: and who is not because any criticism is then painted in the same brush by the other side.

00:27:18.600 --> 00:27:24.880
[Guest]: And somebody, you know, who makes an argument that maybe it is not 4.5, but five would also

00:27:24.880 --> 00:27:26.920
[Guest]: be put in some bracket or the other.

00:27:26.920 --> 00:27:32.440
[Guest]: I think in that case, as a journalist, you know, because I am not an academic now, you

00:27:32.440 --> 00:27:36.240
[Guest]: know, my work as a journalist does not give me the luxury to sort of, you know, go back,

00:27:36.240 --> 00:27:37.880
[Guest]: I'm not saying journalists should not do that.

00:27:37.880 --> 00:27:41.840
[Guest]: You know, sometimes we try and do that, with subjects we like, or we think, you know, we

00:27:41.840 --> 00:27:45.720
[Guest]: can actually make some original contribution to but day to day, it is not possible for

00:27:45.720 --> 00:27:51.040
[Guest]: journalists to take a deep dive into each and every subject, I think then it is important

00:27:51.040 --> 00:27:56.080
[Guest]: to realize at least individually as to what you can and what you cannot do.

00:27:56.080 --> 00:28:00.400
[Guest]: And if beyond the point, there's nothing you can add to the GDP debate.

00:28:00.400 --> 00:28:04.280
[Guest]: Now there are people who have much higher stakes, for example, you know, before the

00:28:04.280 --> 00:28:07.760
[Guest]: RBI monetary policy meetings, Reuters does this poll of economists.

00:28:07.760 --> 00:28:11.800
[Guest]: So now a lot of them have rating agencies, brokering agencies, you know, these trading

00:28:11.800 --> 00:28:14.520
[Guest]: firms, etc, they have started doing their own work.

00:28:14.520 --> 00:28:18.640
[Guest]: So for them, the stakes are higher, they probably can't sort of accept it as fait accompli,

00:28:18.640 --> 00:28:21.800
[Guest]: which we as journalists have to do, unfortunately, that's one.

00:28:21.800 --> 00:28:25.920
[Guest]: But the other thing which you said, you know, is more interesting, because what if data

00:28:25.920 --> 00:28:31.760
[Guest]: sort of doesn't allow you to understand things, you know, or the data which is presented,

00:28:31.760 --> 00:28:35.800
[Guest]: I, let's say the data is not bad, but sometimes data can be half truth.

00:28:35.800 --> 00:28:39.800
[Guest]: You know, for example, because, you know, I write on agriculture often, I consider the

00:28:39.800 --> 00:28:42.680
[Guest]: farmer suicide data to be a classic example of it.

00:28:42.680 --> 00:28:46.280
[Guest]: Now, there's a lot of song and dance about hundreds of 1000s of farmers have committed

00:28:46.280 --> 00:28:49.600
[Guest]: suicide in our country, after economic reforms, etc.

00:28:49.600 --> 00:28:50.600
[Guest]: That is a terrible thing.

00:28:50.600 --> 00:28:53.800
[Guest]: I do not for a moment sort of endorse what has happened.

00:28:53.800 --> 00:28:59.200
[Guest]: But should we as a country take, you know, farmer suicides as the ultimate proof of whether

00:28:59.200 --> 00:29:01.200
[Guest]: or not there exists farmer distress in country.

00:29:01.200 --> 00:29:06.000
[Guest]: Now, most of the farmer suicides in our country, they happen either in Vidarbha or Andhra Pradesh,

00:29:06.000 --> 00:29:08.360
[Guest]: they used to happen in Kerala, Wayanad, etc.

00:29:08.360 --> 00:29:12.640
[Guest]: But so basically, it is commercially driven farmers which commit suicide.

00:29:12.640 --> 00:29:17.920
[Guest]: Now, you will find very few cases of farmer suicides from say Bihar or Eastern Uttar Pradesh,

00:29:17.920 --> 00:29:22.760
[Guest]: which are among the or Odisha or West Bengal, which are among the poorest parts of the country.

00:29:22.760 --> 00:29:26.640
[Guest]: Does that mean that there's no agrarian distress or rural distress in these parts of the country?

00:29:26.640 --> 00:29:31.640
[Guest]: I would say there's probably more rural distress if one were to take into account just poverty

00:29:31.640 --> 00:29:36.280
[Guest]: and sort of inability to make ends meet.

00:29:36.280 --> 00:29:39.880
[Guest]: So why does the farmer suicide data not show in these states because agriculture is driven

00:29:39.880 --> 00:29:44.000
[Guest]: by a completely different set of considerations there, an average farmer in Bihar is only

00:29:44.000 --> 00:29:48.760
[Guest]: interested in, you know, growing enough wheat or rice, probably or a poor lentil to sort

00:29:48.760 --> 00:29:54.480
[Guest]: of grow enough to feed yourself and maybe sell a little and then rest of the time when

00:29:54.480 --> 00:29:58.520
[Guest]: you're not cultivating, you actually go and work as construction worker or something.

00:29:58.520 --> 00:30:04.720
[Guest]: So I think it is in these things where half truths, you know, being captured by data become

00:30:04.720 --> 00:30:10.640
[Guest]: sort of the guiding pole of discussion around very serious issues in our country is where

00:30:10.640 --> 00:30:11.640
[Guest]: we have to be really careful.

00:30:11.640 --> 00:30:13.280
[Guest]: For example, the informal thing.

00:30:13.280 --> 00:30:18.040
[Guest]: Now, I think it is equally important to keep harping upon the fact that we do not know

00:30:18.040 --> 00:30:20.000
[Guest]: what is happening to the informal sector in our country.

00:30:20.000 --> 00:30:23.680
[Guest]: I mean, you have to keep harping upon it and people have to understand that GDP numbers

00:30:23.680 --> 00:30:25.720
[Guest]: probably do not mean a lot for.

00:30:25.720 --> 00:30:31.840
[Guest]: So with the same amount of GDP growth, pre-GST, post-GST life would have become completely

00:30:31.840 --> 00:30:36.040
[Guest]: different for the informal sector in our country, because margins would have taken a deep hit.

00:30:36.040 --> 00:30:40.520
[Guest]: So these are things I think, which have not been emphasized upon adequately, you know,

00:30:40.520 --> 00:30:45.400
[Guest]: and I think Western journalism, you know, things like the Financial Times and a lot

00:30:45.400 --> 00:30:49.200
[Guest]: of other things have a lot of good things to teach us when it comes to journalism.

00:30:49.200 --> 00:30:52.480
[Guest]: And I've always been a believer in the fact that, you know, wherever good things you can

00:30:52.480 --> 00:30:54.560
[Guest]: learn from, you should always learn.

00:30:54.560 --> 00:30:58.960
[Guest]: But to look at and understand a country like India, which still has a very large informal

00:30:58.960 --> 00:31:03.680
[Guest]: sector, a lot of its workforce, almost half of it still depends on agriculture.

00:31:03.680 --> 00:31:10.080
[Guest]: I think in those areas, you know, even the globally established best practices, best

00:31:10.080 --> 00:31:13.800
[Guest]: works, best minds, especially in the journalistic profession cannot help us in understanding

00:31:13.800 --> 00:31:14.800
[Guest]: our country.

00:31:14.800 --> 00:31:18.600
[Guest]: There, you know, there has to be some sort of a concerted effort to develop indigenous

00:31:18.600 --> 00:31:25.040
[Guest]: thinking, indigenous methods, reportage, analysis, whatever that it might be, to help our own

00:31:25.040 --> 00:31:26.120
[Amit Varma]: case, I would say.

00:31:26.120 --> 00:31:30.560
[Amit Varma]: And also, is it like I'm just thinking aloud, you mentioned sort of the farmer suicides.

00:31:30.560 --> 00:31:34.160
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, when you look at data like that, there are so many things you can do

00:31:34.160 --> 00:31:38.040
[Amit Varma]: with that data, you can make different kinds of political cases with that data, depending

00:31:38.040 --> 00:31:42.880
[Amit Varma]: on how you look at it, you can try to contextualize it by saying, okay, if this is a suicide rate

00:31:42.880 --> 00:31:46.160
[Amit Varma]: among farmers, what is the rate among housewives?

00:31:46.160 --> 00:31:48.640
[Amit Varma]: And if it's worse among housewives, what does that mean?

00:31:48.640 --> 00:31:51.920
[Amit Varma]: And should we then ignore the former data, and blah, blah, blah.

00:31:51.920 --> 00:31:58.680
[Amit Varma]: So in that sense, as a journalist, when you're a journalist, do you find that whatever your

00:31:58.680 --> 00:32:01.960
[Amit Varma]: prior inferences might be, or whatever your biases might be?

00:32:01.960 --> 00:32:05.720
[Amit Varma]: Because I mean, frankly, everybody is biased, but you try to be as objective as possible

00:32:05.720 --> 00:32:06.720
[Amit Varma]: in your reportage.

00:32:06.720 --> 00:32:10.920
[Amit Varma]: Of course, but human beings are all biased without exception, but you try to guard against

00:32:10.920 --> 00:32:12.920
[Amit Varma]: bias or be transparent.

00:32:12.920 --> 00:32:18.340
[Amit Varma]: So do those sort of your philosophical leanings and your the principles that you hold also

00:32:18.340 --> 00:32:24.040
[Amit Varma]: then influence the questions that you ask of the data, and therefore influence the directions

00:32:24.040 --> 00:32:25.040
[Guest]: that you go in?

00:32:25.040 --> 00:32:27.560
[Guest]: I think that is the honest way to go about it.

00:32:27.560 --> 00:32:33.520
[Guest]: So the farmer suicide case is a bit straightforward, because thankfully, the NCRB included a subcategory

00:32:33.520 --> 00:32:34.520
[Guest]: in its data.

00:32:34.520 --> 00:32:36.760
[Guest]: So it now lists reason for suicide.

00:32:36.760 --> 00:32:39.640
[Guest]: And if you look at those reasons, actually, you know, most farmers commit suicide due

00:32:39.640 --> 00:32:44.240
[Guest]: to economic distress, crop failure or economic distress, etc.

00:32:44.240 --> 00:32:45.520
[Guest]: That one pretty much stands out.

00:32:45.520 --> 00:32:49.680
[Guest]: Now, let us go into a more controversial topic, let us look at the election results we've

00:32:49.680 --> 00:32:50.680
[Guest]: had to 2019.

00:32:50.680 --> 00:32:54.560
[Guest]: Now, we know that this is a phenomenal victory, which the Bharatiya Janata Party has sort

00:32:54.560 --> 00:32:55.560
[Guest]: of pulled.

00:32:55.560 --> 00:32:59.600
[Guest]: Now, a lot of people, you know, liberals, those leaning on the left would like us to

00:32:59.600 --> 00:33:06.360
[Guest]: believe that, if not all, an overwhelming driver of this victory has been, you know,

00:33:06.360 --> 00:33:09.720
[Guest]: the Bharatiya Janata Party's and its leaders' abilities to sort of polarize the electorate

00:33:09.720 --> 00:33:10.720
[Guest]: and communal lines.

00:33:10.720 --> 00:33:13.200
[Guest]: That is what we are told at least.

00:33:13.200 --> 00:33:17.320
[Guest]: Now, this is something the BJP has been doing for ever since its inception, that that's

00:33:17.320 --> 00:33:21.600
[Guest]: its core politics from Ram Janmabhoomi to many other things.

00:33:21.600 --> 00:33:22.600
[Guest]: Is it just that?

00:33:22.600 --> 00:33:26.600
[Guest]: Or is there more to this victory, you know, it could be national security, it could be

00:33:26.600 --> 00:33:27.600
[Guest]: pro-poor programs.

00:33:27.600 --> 00:33:32.600
[Guest]: Unfortunately, we in India still do not have that kind of detailed, you know, election

00:33:32.600 --> 00:33:33.600
[Guest]: data.

00:33:33.600 --> 00:33:37.600
[Guest]: I mean, the CSDS does some transparent surveys, but the sample size, etc. are still small.

00:33:37.600 --> 00:33:40.400
[Guest]: Those numbers are still not out in the public realm, they probably take their own time to

00:33:40.400 --> 00:33:42.040
[Guest]: release them.

00:33:42.040 --> 00:33:45.560
[Guest]: On questions like these, I think, is where the real test comes.

00:33:45.560 --> 00:33:47.080
[Guest]: Now, what do you do?

00:33:47.080 --> 00:33:49.320
[Guest]: Because there's no easily accessible data.

00:33:49.320 --> 00:33:53.840
[Guest]: You have, you would like to believe, well, let me put it this way, I mean, whether or

00:33:53.840 --> 00:33:57.960
[Guest]: not you'd like to believe there's a convenient set of explanations, you know, which are being

00:33:57.960 --> 00:34:03.760
[Guest]: forwarded by people who are otherwise very established in their academic careers.

00:34:03.760 --> 00:34:04.760
[Guest]: So what do you do?

00:34:04.760 --> 00:34:09.400
[Guest]: I think this is also a challenge for people, you know, who are doing this kind of work

00:34:09.400 --> 00:34:14.560
[Guest]: in our generation, because, you know, if we look at the world today, globally, you know,

00:34:14.560 --> 00:34:16.560
[Guest]: polarization is increasing.

00:34:16.560 --> 00:34:21.040
[Guest]: A lot of leaders, very powerful leaders, I mean, our Prime Minister is one example, we

00:34:21.040 --> 00:34:27.400
[Guest]: have Donald Trump, who are, you know, treading into waters which were considered, I would

00:34:27.400 --> 00:34:30.920
[Guest]: say, the unimaginable, you know, for the United States President to be making the kind of

00:34:30.920 --> 00:34:33.640
[Guest]: statements he's making, etc.

00:34:33.640 --> 00:34:35.400
[Guest]: So these are very different times.

00:34:35.400 --> 00:34:38.160
[Guest]: Economically, these are very difficult times also.

00:34:38.160 --> 00:34:42.560
[Guest]: So we know that economically, things are not going to be as good as they were even 10 years

00:34:42.560 --> 00:34:43.560
[Guest]: ago.

00:34:43.560 --> 00:34:48.120
[Guest]: Now, when there is economic distress, when there is a lot of polarization already happening,

00:34:48.120 --> 00:34:49.400
[Guest]: how do you explain the world?

00:34:49.400 --> 00:34:51.160
[Guest]: How do you even try and engage with the world?

00:34:51.160 --> 00:34:54.960
[Guest]: Now, data can be one bit, but I think the correct approach as far as, you know, or at

00:34:54.960 --> 00:34:59.680
[Guest]: least the one which I try and take is, I mean, look at the data, because that's not at least

00:34:59.680 --> 00:35:04.080
[Guest]: sacrosanct and the good part in India is, you know, most of the data actually comes

00:35:04.080 --> 00:35:05.080
[Guest]: from the government.

00:35:05.080 --> 00:35:08.960
[Guest]: So if you're using the government's own data, there's only a limit to which people can disagree

00:35:08.960 --> 00:35:11.960
[Guest]: with you, including those, you know, in the government.

00:35:11.960 --> 00:35:13.840
[Guest]: So that's the good part about using data.

00:35:13.840 --> 00:35:19.040
[Guest]: But I think then one also has to have a very sort of open mind, you know, you asked me

00:35:19.040 --> 00:35:24.520
[Guest]: the question earlier about which are the thinkers I would sort of, I draw my thoughts from,

00:35:24.520 --> 00:35:29.720
[Guest]: I think, you know, the kind of world we are in today, and there's not one thinker, who

00:35:29.720 --> 00:35:33.340
[Guest]: you can use to sort of explain the world, you know, for example, let us look at somebody

00:35:33.340 --> 00:35:35.080
[Guest]: like Bawasaheb Ambedkar.

00:35:35.080 --> 00:35:42.160
[Guest]: I think in today's India, if there's one politician slash leader who is admired by everybody across

00:35:42.160 --> 00:35:46.880
[Guest]: the political spectrum, now, the RSS, BJP has a lot of problems with Jawaharlal Nehru,

00:35:46.880 --> 00:35:50.080
[Guest]: I mean, they do not say so explicitly, but they have a lot of problems with a lot of

00:35:50.080 --> 00:35:51.720
[Guest]: things Mahatma Gandhi also did.

00:35:51.720 --> 00:35:55.840
[Guest]: But Bawasaheb Ambedkar is one person with whom everybody now the communists also used

00:35:55.840 --> 00:35:59.840
[Guest]: to be critical of him earlier from from the from the ultra left to the ultra right sort

00:35:59.840 --> 00:36:01.960
[Guest]: of eulogizes Bawasaheb Ambedkar.

00:36:01.960 --> 00:36:05.920
[Guest]: If you were to read his writings in entirety, I think Bawasaheb would be the most hated

00:36:05.920 --> 00:36:09.600
[Guest]: political figure in this country today, because he's really spoken in mind and all sorts of

00:36:09.600 --> 00:36:10.600
[Amit Varma]: issues.

00:36:10.600 --> 00:36:12.880
[Guest]: In fact, especially hated by the Hindu right wing.

00:36:12.880 --> 00:36:13.880
[Guest]: Exactly.

00:36:13.880 --> 00:36:17.920
[Guest]: Difficult to say a lot of people would hate him for a lot of reasons.

00:36:17.920 --> 00:36:20.920
[Guest]: So, you know, I have been trained in a leftist tradition.

00:36:20.920 --> 00:36:25.400
[Guest]: So I of course think you know that the basic thing you know, which sort of Marx Lenin etc

00:36:25.400 --> 00:36:30.440
[Guest]: still holds a lot of, but, you know, you could say that you draw your basic larger analysis

00:36:30.440 --> 00:36:34.120
[Guest]: from the Marxian scheme, but there's no socialism in today's world.

00:36:34.120 --> 00:36:39.920
[Guest]: I mean, I cannot envisage a socialism which does not allow me free markets, or that basically,

00:36:39.920 --> 00:36:44.280
[Guest]: but no, a lot of people on the left today celebrate basic liberties, what kind of civil

00:36:44.280 --> 00:36:47.160
[Guest]: liberties did the Soviet Union allow to its people?

00:36:47.160 --> 00:36:49.480
[Guest]: What kind of civil liberties does China allow to its people?

00:36:49.480 --> 00:36:53.280
[Guest]: I mean, you say our country, you know, this communal politics, etc, look at what China

00:36:53.280 --> 00:36:56.140
[Guest]: is doing to Muslims who have been put in those camps.

00:36:56.140 --> 00:37:00.680
[Guest]: So I do not think there's a grand narrative today, which fits the world.

00:37:00.680 --> 00:37:05.860
[Guest]: But I also think that, and it'll probably become more important, I think we have to

00:37:05.860 --> 00:37:09.320
[Guest]: the fact that India and you know, my formal training is in economics.

00:37:09.320 --> 00:37:14.720
[Guest]: So my knowledge of history and know politics in relatively much poor compared to what the

00:37:14.720 --> 00:37:17.000
[Guest]: student of politics or history would have.

00:37:17.000 --> 00:37:21.480
[Guest]: But the more I try and read about it, the more I get fascinated with the fact that India

00:37:21.480 --> 00:37:25.240
[Guest]: as it were, we were able to arrive at this constitutional consensus to sort of adopt

00:37:25.240 --> 00:37:26.240
[Guest]: a constitution.

00:37:26.240 --> 00:37:29.800
[Guest]: And what we have managed is, of course, in the third world, sort of unparalleled, I mean,

00:37:29.800 --> 00:37:35.160
[Guest]: we look at our neighbors, we look at other third world countries, emerging markets, etc.

00:37:35.160 --> 00:37:40.680
[Guest]: without a political shock to our democracy, barring the emergency, which also, you know,

00:37:40.680 --> 00:37:44.000
[Guest]: the transition to democracy was, I would say, relatively much more peaceful than what other

00:37:44.000 --> 00:37:47.520
[Guest]: countries have had to have without a major economic crisis.

00:37:47.520 --> 00:37:51.440
[Guest]: And no, when we talk about the 91 balance of payment crisis, etc.

00:37:51.440 --> 00:37:54.600
[Guest]: But that basically involved shipping some gold from here to London, I mean, look at

00:37:54.600 --> 00:37:58.040
[Guest]: the kind of economic crisis East Asian countries have had Latin American countries have to

00:37:58.040 --> 00:37:59.040
[Guest]: add.

00:37:59.040 --> 00:38:03.640
[Guest]: So by and large, we have, you know, emerged pretty much sort of unharmed.

00:38:03.640 --> 00:38:05.840
[Guest]: Now, I think India has to change.

00:38:05.840 --> 00:38:11.200
[Guest]: I mean, it can't be the way it has been, for example, is something I always say, you know,

00:38:11.200 --> 00:38:15.120
[Guest]: so a lot of people on the left today say that if you want to counter Narendra Modi, you

00:38:15.120 --> 00:38:18.880
[Guest]: have to have a Bernie Sanders or you have to have a Jeremy Corbyn, etc.

00:38:18.880 --> 00:38:23.800
[Guest]: Now, for people like say, Sanders or Corbyn to be able to know indulge in the kind of

00:38:23.800 --> 00:38:27.760
[Guest]: rhetoric they are doing, and you know, a lot of which I agree with, but that is besides

00:38:27.760 --> 00:38:28.760
[Guest]: the point.

00:38:28.760 --> 00:38:34.000
[Guest]: I think it draws traction from the fact that both the United States, UK, etc, they at least

00:38:34.000 --> 00:38:39.680
[Guest]: know after the Second World War had a golden age, I mean, where social security, education,

00:38:39.680 --> 00:38:42.240
[Guest]: economy, everything was in a really good shape.

00:38:42.240 --> 00:38:44.440
[Guest]: I don't think that was the case in India ever.

00:38:44.440 --> 00:38:51.360
[Guest]: So if one were to ask, you know, say, intergenerationally or otherwise, also, I do not think there are

00:38:51.360 --> 00:38:55.560
[Guest]: a handful of people, you know, who who might be like that, but most people are actually

00:38:55.560 --> 00:38:58.920
[Guest]: materially well off in India even today compared to what they were earlier.

00:38:58.920 --> 00:39:01.080
[Guest]: So we need to have a different kind of a theory for it.

00:39:01.080 --> 00:39:05.400
[Guest]: I mean, this is something I dwelt on in my last piece also, I mean, class in the classic

00:39:05.400 --> 00:39:10.400
[Guest]: sense of the term as we stand it, for example, in the old left rhetoric of Tata, Billa, etc.

00:39:10.400 --> 00:39:14.600
[Guest]: I mean, today, Adani Ambani has replaced the Tata Billa.

00:39:14.600 --> 00:39:19.240
[Guest]: I think the average man on the person on the street loves Mukesh Ambani for the geophones

00:39:19.240 --> 00:39:22.800
[Amit Varma]: because, you know, we have cheapest data in our country today, or for the Mumbai Indians

00:39:22.800 --> 00:39:28.440
[Guest]: entertainment where you could be but talking in terms of materially, I mean, telecom revolution

00:39:28.440 --> 00:39:34.240
[Guest]: in our country, IT revolution in our country, these are all genuine capitalist driven innovations

00:39:34.240 --> 00:39:36.240
[Guest]: which are which our country has really exploited.

00:39:36.240 --> 00:39:40.600
[Guest]: We talk of the IT boom today, you know, I talked about JNU, for example, I said, you

00:39:40.600 --> 00:39:46.520
[Guest]: know, JNU, you know, being cheap fees, etc, subsidized education that it was, but JNU has

00:39:46.520 --> 00:39:48.560
[Guest]: only produced a handful of people like me.

00:39:48.560 --> 00:39:52.600
[Guest]: If we talk about our success in the IT boom, because of which a lot of remittances come

00:39:52.600 --> 00:39:57.080
[Guest]: into our country, a lot of people in my generation, our generation are employed in those sectors.

00:39:57.080 --> 00:39:59.040
[Guest]: This was these are all private engineering colleges.

00:39:59.040 --> 00:40:02.920
[Guest]: I mean, your IITs could only have produced so many graduates, I mean, thousands and thousands

00:40:02.920 --> 00:40:06.920
[Guest]: of engineering graduates which we are producing, because of private sector in education.

00:40:06.920 --> 00:40:12.080
[Guest]: So I think, you know, there have to be certain things which are sacrosanct, civil liberty

00:40:12.080 --> 00:40:15.960
[Guest]: should be one, basic health and education should be one.

00:40:15.960 --> 00:40:20.880
[Guest]: But you largely have to have a political framework, even if, you know, you want to criticize any

00:40:20.880 --> 00:40:25.120
[Guest]: regime, be it this regime or the earlier regime or the next regime which comes.

00:40:25.120 --> 00:40:31.120
[Guest]: I think you have to have a way to sort of evolve on your existing successes.

00:40:31.120 --> 00:40:35.720
[Guest]: In case of India, in case of, you know, for example, you know, there were 1,001 million

00:40:35.720 --> 00:40:38.800
[Guest]: problems with the Soviet Union, but it did certain good things to the world.

00:40:38.800 --> 00:40:42.480
[Guest]: There was universal suffrage after the Soviet Union came into being, etc.

00:40:42.480 --> 00:40:46.440
[Guest]: So I think the successes of the past have to be sort of, I mean, imbibed.

00:40:46.440 --> 00:40:50.440
[Guest]: And then you can't ask for going back to say the past.

00:40:50.440 --> 00:40:54.440
[Guest]: That is how I think political thinking has to evolve in our country, especially in today's

00:40:54.440 --> 00:40:55.440
[Guest]: times.

00:40:55.440 --> 00:40:58.240
[Guest]: You have to know what I mean, for example, I would love to read all of what Bawasabha

00:40:58.240 --> 00:41:01.840
[Guest]: Medkar said, I would love to read more about the Constituent Assembly debates, I've not

00:41:01.840 --> 00:41:03.580
[Guest]: read about them at all.

00:41:03.580 --> 00:41:07.240
[Guest]: But you have to bring those kinds of debates into focus.

00:41:07.240 --> 00:41:08.240
[Guest]: What is at stake?

00:41:08.240 --> 00:41:10.760
[Guest]: How did we agree on what we actually agreed on?

00:41:10.760 --> 00:41:15.440
[Guest]: Were there pending disagreements about important things which were, you know, where the attitude

00:41:15.440 --> 00:41:18.480
[Guest]: of the political class was, so to say, kick the can down the road?

00:41:18.480 --> 00:41:22.200
[Guest]: I think those kinds of debates have to be revived today have to be engaged with to be

00:41:22.200 --> 00:41:26.200
[Guest]: able to construct any meaningful political civil discourse in our country.

00:41:26.200 --> 00:41:30.920
[Amit Varma]: I think what I largely find and this is a lament is that instead of a deepening of the

00:41:30.920 --> 00:41:36.000
[Amit Varma]: discourse, the way you just mentioned, what we are seeing is a shallowing out of the discourse

00:41:36.000 --> 00:41:41.200
[Amit Varma]: where at least in the public discourse, what you see is increasing polarizations as people

00:41:41.200 --> 00:41:45.920
[Amit Varma]: take essentially tribal positions, which, you know, brings me back to your earlier point

00:41:45.920 --> 00:41:52.780
[Amit Varma]: that you made that, you know, that when you take something like these 2019 election results,

00:41:52.780 --> 00:41:56.520
[Amit Varma]: and they can be interpreted in so many different ways, and people will just stick whatever

00:41:56.520 --> 00:42:00.640
[Amit Varma]: narrative they want on it, where some people will say this shows that India is bigoted,

00:42:00.640 --> 00:42:04.000
[Amit Varma]: and some people will, you know, you can make different narratives out of it.

00:42:04.000 --> 00:42:08.020
[Amit Varma]: And all of which may be true or false to different degrees.

00:42:08.020 --> 00:42:13.120
[Amit Varma]: But the question here is that, even as a journalist, when you work with data for either journalists

00:42:13.120 --> 00:42:18.200
[Amit Varma]: or public intellectuals, there's also partly the expectation that in some way, you will

00:42:18.200 --> 00:42:20.600
[Amit Varma]: help to make sense of the world.

00:42:20.600 --> 00:42:25.640
[Amit Varma]: And in some way, that will involve creating perhaps a narrative of your own, however,

00:42:25.640 --> 00:42:28.000
[Amit Varma]: it might be more nuanced than the other narratives out there.

00:42:28.000 --> 00:42:31.080
[Amit Varma]: But however, nuanced, it might be creating a narrative.

00:42:31.080 --> 00:42:36.440
[Amit Varma]: And my question when you work with data is that, in the social sciences, how easy is

00:42:36.440 --> 00:42:37.440
[Amit Varma]: it to do that?

00:42:37.440 --> 00:42:42.920
[Amit Varma]: For example, I mean, it's very hard to when you talk about public policy to infer causation,

00:42:42.920 --> 00:42:47.160
[Amit Varma]: and you know, figure out what is causation and what is merely correlation, like an economist

00:42:47.160 --> 00:42:50.840
[Amit Varma]: who's been a frequent guest on my show, Shruti Rajagopal, and she once gave me a really good

00:42:50.840 --> 00:42:52.180
[Amit Varma]: example of this.

00:42:52.180 --> 00:42:57.080
[Amit Varma]: She said, let's say you want to figure out if dropping a coin in water will raise the

00:42:57.080 --> 00:42:58.720
[Amit Varma]: level of the water or not.

00:42:58.720 --> 00:43:02.240
[Amit Varma]: Now you can arrive at it through scientific first principles and say that, yeah, of course

00:43:02.240 --> 00:43:03.240
[Amit Varma]: it will.

00:43:03.240 --> 00:43:04.600
[Amit Varma]: Or you can say, we'll do an experiment.

00:43:04.600 --> 00:43:08.320
[Amit Varma]: And within a lab and control conditions, you take a beaker of water, you measure the length,

00:43:08.320 --> 00:43:12.120
[Amit Varma]: you put a coin, you measure the height again, and you know what it is.

00:43:12.120 --> 00:43:16.280
[Amit Varma]: But in social sciences, the equivalent of that is you are in a large swimming pool with

00:43:16.280 --> 00:43:20.760
[Amit Varma]: many people bobbing in and out, and you drop a coin in that swimming pool.

00:43:20.760 --> 00:43:23.160
[Amit Varma]: And then you try to measure the height of the water.

00:43:23.160 --> 00:43:26.120
[Amit Varma]: And sometimes it will be up, sometimes it will be down.

00:43:26.120 --> 00:43:28.840
[Amit Varma]: On what basis are you going to infer causation?

00:43:28.840 --> 00:43:34.480
[Amit Varma]: So when you look at all the data that emerges out of our madly messy society and our madly

00:43:34.480 --> 00:43:39.440
[Amit Varma]: messy economy, isn't that a sort of a problem that you face that you are supposed to make

00:43:39.440 --> 00:43:40.680
[Amit Varma]: sense of all of this?

00:43:40.680 --> 00:43:42.920
[Amit Varma]: But I mean, how do you handle that challenge?

00:43:42.920 --> 00:43:44.840
[Guest]: There are two, three ways about it.

00:43:44.840 --> 00:43:51.040
[Guest]: First, like you said, I think, even today, you know, it might seem a cliche for the people

00:43:51.040 --> 00:43:52.760
[Guest]: who actually know the subject.

00:43:52.760 --> 00:43:58.040
[Guest]: I think as journalists, it is our duty not to sort of engage with, you know, the experts

00:43:58.040 --> 00:44:03.320
[Guest]: or the converted, but to the larger audience, which in India, I still believe, sincerely

00:44:03.320 --> 00:44:08.960
[Guest]: looks up to journalism to give them information as unbiased as it can be.

00:44:08.960 --> 00:44:14.320
[Guest]: So I think the most important point is to reiterate the first principles.

00:44:14.320 --> 00:44:18.840
[Guest]: We have to know what I or you might take for granted, you know, in terms of even inferring

00:44:18.840 --> 00:44:22.960
[Guest]: the data that we have, sort of go out and educate the larger audiences.

00:44:22.960 --> 00:44:27.880
[Guest]: For example, a couple of years ago, for Hindustan Times, on the day of the budget, we actually

00:44:27.880 --> 00:44:30.560
[Guest]: did a large data piece explaining the basic things.

00:44:30.560 --> 00:44:34.120
[Guest]: For example, what does a revised estimate and a budget estimate mean?

00:44:34.120 --> 00:44:35.120
[Guest]: For us, it's obvious.

00:44:35.120 --> 00:44:36.120
[Guest]: I mean, we know it.

00:44:36.120 --> 00:44:39.480
[Guest]: But I think for the larger audience, even those bits of knowledge, I mean, we should

00:44:39.480 --> 00:44:43.680
[Guest]: at no point of time consider explaining these basic things beneath us.

00:44:43.680 --> 00:44:45.680
[Guest]: That I think is the first requirement of being a journalist.

00:44:45.680 --> 00:44:48.680
[Guest]: You have to know you engage with at a very mass level.

00:44:48.680 --> 00:44:54.640
[Guest]: The second thing is, I think what you said to point that out, that this is what actually

00:44:54.640 --> 00:45:01.520
[Guest]: can happen now, because inflation under this government was, you know, very low, it doesn't

00:45:01.520 --> 00:45:04.200
[Guest]: mean that all of it was a policy success.

00:45:04.200 --> 00:45:08.000
[Guest]: Inflation was low also, because this government enjoyed for a very large part of it, the previous

00:45:08.000 --> 00:45:13.160
[Guest]: government low oil prices, something as basic as that has to be explained.

00:45:13.160 --> 00:45:16.040
[Guest]: I mean, bonds, the government is planning to issue them.

00:45:16.040 --> 00:45:20.920
[Guest]: So a lot of people have written against it, a lot of people have written in favor of it.

00:45:20.920 --> 00:45:25.600
[Guest]: I would like to do a piece at some point of time, you know, something as basic as this,

00:45:25.600 --> 00:45:30.720
[Guest]: that note, you borrow $5 billion today, the exchange rate is 70 for $1 today, you expect

00:45:30.720 --> 00:45:35.200
[Guest]: it to be 75 for $1 when you have to repay that loan in say five years, what if the exchange

00:45:35.200 --> 00:45:40.960
[Guest]: rate were to be 90 per dollar, then the kind of money you have to pay, I mean, would increase

00:45:40.960 --> 00:45:41.960
[Guest]: many folds.

00:45:41.960 --> 00:45:44.720
[Guest]: Similarly, if the exchange rate were to go down, it probably make a windfall.

00:45:44.720 --> 00:45:47.760
[Guest]: Then you go to another data point as to how the rupee has behaved.

00:45:47.760 --> 00:45:52.800
[Guest]: So I think a step by step narrative, counting all the possibilities, which might or might

00:45:52.800 --> 00:45:58.280
[Guest]: not happen, actually, this is my experience personally, for example, I am the happiest

00:45:58.280 --> 00:46:03.240
[Guest]: when one day I write a piece in ST, then some class 11 student from say Jalandhar writes

00:46:03.240 --> 00:46:06.320
[Guest]: a mail to me, then I really like this, I want to be a journalist, etc.

00:46:06.320 --> 00:46:07.320
[Guest]: Has that happened?

00:46:07.320 --> 00:46:08.320
[Guest]: Sometimes it does happen.

00:46:08.320 --> 00:46:11.280
[Guest]: So that is what I really look forward to, because the experts, you know, I'm very grateful

00:46:11.280 --> 00:46:15.720
[Guest]: to them that they promote my work, etc. but that is something where I do not have to make

00:46:15.720 --> 00:46:17.560
[Guest]: an extra effort to sort of go and engage with them.

00:46:17.560 --> 00:46:22.480
[Guest]: That is their subject of interest, they like it, they, you know, sometimes they also engage

00:46:22.480 --> 00:46:26.240
[Guest]: with me to sort of promote me, encourage me, develop my own arguments.

00:46:26.240 --> 00:46:32.920
[Guest]: But when I'm able to engage with a intelligent layperson reader, by not compromising the

00:46:32.920 --> 00:46:37.000
[Guest]: basic method I do in my story writing is when I feel the happiest and I think that the future

00:46:37.000 --> 00:46:40.280
[Guest]: for these kind of arguments to be made more and more people should be making it.

00:46:40.280 --> 00:46:44.080
[Amit Varma]: So what you're saying is that your work is not just you don't view your work just as

00:46:44.080 --> 00:46:49.440
[Amit Varma]: interpreting data and coming up with an explanation or a narrative of how things are, but also

00:46:49.440 --> 00:46:54.240
[Amit Varma]: helping people see how the different kinds of data interact with each other, and therefore

00:46:54.240 --> 00:46:59.320
[Amit Varma]: helping them better understand the complexity of it that the complexity of the swimming

00:46:59.320 --> 00:47:00.320
[Amit Varma]: pool for that matter.

00:47:00.320 --> 00:47:01.320
[Guest]: And right.

00:47:01.320 --> 00:47:05.940
[Guest]: So, you know, as you mentioned earlier, I have this past as a political activist.

00:47:05.940 --> 00:47:08.520
[Guest]: So knowing genuine, it's very common with the left.

00:47:08.520 --> 00:47:11.520
[Guest]: So Marx has this famous quote of philosophers have only interpreted the world.

00:47:11.520 --> 00:47:13.840
[Guest]: The point, however, is to change it.

00:47:13.840 --> 00:47:17.120
[Guest]: I think when you're a journalist, only the first part of the phrase applies to you.

00:47:17.120 --> 00:47:22.160
[Guest]: Your job is basically to interpret the world as well as you can, and list all possibilities.

00:47:22.160 --> 00:47:23.560
[Amit Varma]: But you're basically helping change it also.

00:47:23.560 --> 00:47:30.040
[Amit Varma]: I mean, that boy in Jalandhar who wrote to you and you might one day go on to.

00:47:30.040 --> 00:47:32.320
[Guest]: But I think this is also an extremely important thing.

00:47:32.320 --> 00:47:35.440
[Guest]: And this is something I believe because you know, I've been on the other side of the world

00:47:35.440 --> 00:47:40.400
[Guest]: as a political activist, and today I'm a journalist, and I think, you know, unless and until you're

00:47:40.400 --> 00:47:42.920
[Guest]: writing opinion, there should not be an overlap in these two.

00:47:42.920 --> 00:47:45.720
[Guest]: I mean, it is important for unbiased journalism.

00:47:45.720 --> 00:47:50.560
[Guest]: But I think as journalists, we also need to understand that, you know, just because we

00:47:50.560 --> 00:47:55.480
[Guest]: think and we always try to be writing what the truth is, it doesn't mean it'll have automatic

00:47:55.480 --> 00:47:56.720
[Guest]: traction in the society.

00:47:56.720 --> 00:48:00.400
[Guest]: Now, this is something which is not rocket science, a lot of philosophers, etc.

00:48:00.400 --> 00:48:04.200
[Guest]: Marx has written on it that, you know, no matter whether an idea is true or false, the

00:48:04.200 --> 00:48:09.120
[Guest]: kind of social traction, political traction it has, also depends on larger social conditions,

00:48:09.120 --> 00:48:10.640
[Guest]: political conditions, etc.

00:48:10.640 --> 00:48:14.680
[Guest]: So if you have that in mind, then it gives you a certain amount of I would say critical

00:48:14.680 --> 00:48:19.500
[Guest]: distance or whatever one might call it, or no, or the ability to work very dispassionately

00:48:19.500 --> 00:48:21.240
[Guest]: and objectively also.

00:48:21.240 --> 00:48:25.560
[Guest]: That is something I consider myself lucky to have developed that thing early in my career.

00:48:25.560 --> 00:48:30.400
[Amit Varma]: And as someone who looks at data on a daily basis, and perhaps reflexively, you look at

00:48:30.400 --> 00:48:35.160
[Amit Varma]: the data in every subject that you do, do you look at columnists and opinion writers

00:48:35.160 --> 00:48:39.640
[Amit Varma]: like myself, for example, and think ki yaar yeh hawa mein baat kar rahe hain, matlab it's

00:48:39.640 --> 00:48:44.720
[Amit Varma]: not grounded in, because then it must seem very easy for anyone to just sit down and

00:48:44.720 --> 00:48:46.160
[Amit Varma]: write an opinion column, right?

00:48:46.160 --> 00:48:50.640
[Amit Varma]: Because if they don't have to back it up with data, whereas your work is around data, everything

00:48:50.640 --> 00:48:51.640
[Amit Varma]: is around data.

00:48:51.640 --> 00:48:57.640
[Amit Varma]: So does it change the way you look at other opinion writers, columnists, all of that?

00:48:57.640 --> 00:49:03.240
[Guest]: So my newspaper, my idea of a newspaper, and this has never changed, you know, when I was

00:49:03.240 --> 00:49:07.080
[Guest]: standing at five or six, and I used to read a Hindi newspaper, today I read a lot of newspapers,

00:49:07.080 --> 00:49:09.080
[Guest]: I would probably like to read even more.

00:49:09.080 --> 00:49:12.440
[Guest]: So my newspaper always used to finish at the op-ed pages.

00:49:12.440 --> 00:49:16.440
[Guest]: So business, foreign, sports, I never looked at them throughout my life.

00:49:16.440 --> 00:49:20.680
[Guest]: Now that I work in a newspaper, I realize how important they are.

00:49:20.680 --> 00:49:25.560
[Guest]: So I think one thing which newspapers teach you is plurality and diversity of views is

00:49:25.560 --> 00:49:27.960
[Guest]: extremely important.

00:49:27.960 --> 00:49:31.560
[Guest]: And when I say views, I do not just mean views, I also mean work, you know, because, you know,

00:49:31.560 --> 00:49:35.920
[Guest]: I might be doing data, somebody might be covering the BJP, somebody who might be looking at

00:49:35.920 --> 00:49:40.840
[Guest]: personal finance, business papers have more than one reporter just tracking mutual funds.

00:49:40.840 --> 00:49:45.280
[Guest]: I think, you know, all of those works are extremely important, including people who

00:49:45.280 --> 00:49:50.080
[Guest]: write opinion pieces, because what it allows a journalist is, you know, like I said earlier,

00:49:50.080 --> 00:49:56.800
[Guest]: I think good journalism in this country, even today has a lot of potential to bring intellect

00:49:56.800 --> 00:49:58.400
[Guest]: levels up in our society.

00:49:58.400 --> 00:50:04.600
[Guest]: Now, I might never have read a, what should I say, even the basic, you know, text of Ambedkar,

00:50:04.600 --> 00:50:09.440
[Guest]: I have not read much of it, but a lot of people when they write, the fact that there exists

00:50:09.440 --> 00:50:14.000
[Guest]: something like a constituent assembly debate, the fact that there was a debate on cow protection,

00:50:14.000 --> 00:50:17.920
[Guest]: you know, in our country, when the constitution was being made, these are all things I've

00:50:17.920 --> 00:50:20.600
[Guest]: learned from newspaper writings, popular writings.

00:50:20.600 --> 00:50:23.720
[Guest]: I think this is where public intellectuals have a role to play.

00:50:23.720 --> 00:50:27.000
[Guest]: And public intellectuals need not only be in universities or very high ranking think

00:50:27.000 --> 00:50:28.000
[Guest]: tanks.

00:50:28.000 --> 00:50:30.400
[Guest]: I think this is where all of us are public intellectuals have a very important role to

00:50:30.400 --> 00:50:31.400
[Guest]: play.

00:50:31.400 --> 00:50:35.960
[Guest]: We have to learn to agree to disagree, I will not agree with everything you say, etc.

00:50:35.960 --> 00:50:39.960
[Guest]: But even then, I think it is extremely important, especially in today's conditions, when there

00:50:39.960 --> 00:50:45.680
[Guest]: is a lot of social polarization, political polarization, that we get to engage, for example,

00:50:45.680 --> 00:50:50.560
[Guest]: I would personally like to know a lot more about what Dindayal Upadhyay's writings are.

00:50:50.560 --> 00:50:52.120
[Guest]: Unfortunately, I've never read them.

00:50:52.120 --> 00:50:56.640
[Guest]: But no, when we have a prime minister, who's probably one of the most popular leaders in

00:50:56.640 --> 00:51:00.880
[Guest]: my generation, the most popular leader, because I never saw Mrs. Gandhi, who swears by Dindayal

00:51:00.880 --> 00:51:04.280
[Guest]: Upadhyay's ideology, who claims that the BJP is driven by Dindayal, I think there's some

00:51:04.280 --> 00:51:05.640
[Guest]: merit in engaging with that.

00:51:05.640 --> 00:51:09.560
[Guest]: So I would actually love to have a lot more people writing on what Dindayal Upadhyay wrote.

00:51:09.560 --> 00:51:13.440
[Guest]: Now, you have to, there's good work in journalism, there's bad work in journalism, there's good

00:51:13.440 --> 00:51:16.320
[Guest]: opinion writing, there's bad opinion writing.

00:51:16.320 --> 00:51:20.160
[Guest]: But I think this is one of the beauties of free market and society, which has, I think,

00:51:20.160 --> 00:51:23.520
[Guest]: a lot of freedom to write, read, engage, etc.

00:51:23.520 --> 00:51:26.680
[Guest]: You can always go out and choose what you want to, I mean, the Indian journalistic scene

00:51:26.680 --> 00:51:31.840
[Guest]: to me, I mean, is that we don't have a Walmart in country, but this is the Walmart of ideas,

00:51:31.840 --> 00:51:36.240
[Guest]: I think, I mean, you can go and look at what you want to buy and don't want to buy.

00:51:36.240 --> 00:51:37.240
[Guest]: I think it's very important.

00:51:37.240 --> 00:51:39.760
[Amit Varma]: No, and that's beautifully said, and that strikes a chord with me also.

00:51:39.760 --> 00:51:44.120
[Amit Varma]: And what you said about having that multiplicity of kinds of journalism and ideas and all of

00:51:44.120 --> 00:51:48.840
[Amit Varma]: that in a newspaper where you have a business page, a foreign page, and I usually go to

00:51:48.840 --> 00:51:51.760
[Amit Varma]: the sports page first, so kindly judge me for it.

00:51:51.760 --> 00:51:57.200
[Amit Varma]: But it doesn't worry you that in modern times, how people interact with content is changing

00:51:57.200 --> 00:52:02.080
[Amit Varma]: to the extent that all of this is getting sort of, like earlier, what used to happen

00:52:02.080 --> 00:52:05.720
[Amit Varma]: is that you get a daily newspaper at home, and everything is there is available to you

00:52:05.720 --> 00:52:09.800
[Amit Varma]: when you flip through it, and you know, you may or may not read some things, but they're

00:52:09.800 --> 00:52:10.800
[Amit Varma]: all available for you.

00:52:10.800 --> 00:52:15.160
[Amit Varma]: And today, the way people discover content, discover media is mostly you'll go on Facebook

00:52:15.160 --> 00:52:20.000
[Amit Varma]: or you follow a link on social media is all been kind of this aggregated, you don't get

00:52:20.000 --> 00:52:22.920
[Amit Varma]: these filtered packages coming to you.

00:52:22.920 --> 00:52:26.600
[Amit Varma]: Instead, you get I mean, there's a different kind of filter which comes at you from social

00:52:26.600 --> 00:52:32.120
[Amit Varma]: media, it might even be a tribal filter, because social media is so increasingly polarized.

00:52:32.120 --> 00:52:38.240
[Amit Varma]: And a lot of people are being exposed, therefore, to only one specific kind of content and not

00:52:38.240 --> 00:52:43.360
[Amit Varma]: to that broad, diverse sort of content that is there in our newspapers.

00:52:43.360 --> 00:52:48.040
[Amit Varma]: Is that something that I may be overstating or is it something that worries you for the

00:52:48.040 --> 00:52:49.040
[Amit Varma]: future?

00:52:49.040 --> 00:52:53.200
[Guest]: It should not happen in principle is something I agree on.

00:52:53.200 --> 00:52:58.600
[Guest]: But you see, there are certain things which, you know, you have to take them as they come.

00:52:58.600 --> 00:53:02.800
[Guest]: But I would say I mean, there was a time when there were no newspapers, the time when there

00:53:02.800 --> 00:53:07.520
[Guest]: were no courts in our country, there was no, I mean, not just our country everywhere, society

00:53:07.520 --> 00:53:08.520
[Guest]: has evolved.

00:53:08.520 --> 00:53:11.080
[Guest]: So I think the news industry is also evolving today.

00:53:11.080 --> 00:53:14.760
[Guest]: And there are no, I mean, you are only talking about the desirability aspect of it.

00:53:14.760 --> 00:53:18.960
[Guest]: I mean, all of us who work in media know that there's a very big revenue aspect to it also.

00:53:18.960 --> 00:53:19.960
[Guest]: Exactly.

00:53:19.960 --> 00:53:21.360
[Guest]: Traditional business models in media are struggling.

00:53:21.360 --> 00:53:23.200
[Guest]: Now I'm not somebody who understands a lot of it.

00:53:23.200 --> 00:53:26.320
[Guest]: But working in a company, I know that how difficult things are today for everybody in

00:53:26.320 --> 00:53:27.820
[Guest]: the media industry.

00:53:27.820 --> 00:53:32.240
[Guest]: How we'll deal with those challenges, time will tell, there are more capable people than

00:53:32.240 --> 00:53:35.040
[Guest]: me who would have to deal with these challenges.

00:53:35.040 --> 00:53:38.680
[Guest]: I mean, free market also means that the ones who adapt survive, the ones who do not probably

00:53:38.680 --> 00:53:40.360
[Guest]: do not survive.

00:53:40.360 --> 00:53:46.400
[Guest]: But like I said, though, when I talk about it in terms of pure desirability, I think

00:53:46.400 --> 00:53:52.360
[Guest]: the casualty which, you know, causation which one draws is that because, you know, Facebook

00:53:52.360 --> 00:53:55.420
[Guest]: and WhatsApp and fake news and videos, etc, are happening.

00:53:55.420 --> 00:53:58.960
[Guest]: This is why a certain kind of politics is sort of gaining traction in India, in the

00:53:58.960 --> 00:54:01.680
[Guest]: world, etc.

00:54:01.680 --> 00:54:05.560
[Guest]: I think that's partly true, but that's also not true.

00:54:05.560 --> 00:54:10.920
[Guest]: The basic premise, you know, if you follow the sort of Marxian scheme of analysis is

00:54:10.920 --> 00:54:17.160
[Guest]: that, you know, you were able to make a revolution in 1917, because majority of the people agreed

00:54:17.160 --> 00:54:22.520
[Guest]: with the basic cause you were espousing, when Lenin said land, peace and bread, so many

00:54:22.520 --> 00:54:28.000
[Guest]: people in what was then Russia later became Soviet Union came with him, made a revolution.

00:54:28.000 --> 00:54:35.640
[Guest]: Today, if your premise is that, you know, I think OBC, you know, phrased it in the best

00:54:35.640 --> 00:54:38.680
[Guest]: possible way that the Hindu mind has been hijacked.

00:54:38.680 --> 00:54:40.880
[Guest]: I think you can't stop there.

00:54:40.880 --> 00:54:45.240
[Guest]: I mean, if you believe and you know, I think there's an objective basis to saying that

00:54:45.240 --> 00:54:49.320
[Guest]: a lot of people are financially in trouble, things are not as good as they were before

00:54:49.320 --> 00:54:53.320
[Guest]: the crisis, a lot of our young generation who are getting out of colleges, universities,

00:54:53.320 --> 00:54:55.800
[Guest]: etc, are not finding jobs.

00:54:55.800 --> 00:55:00.800
[Guest]: Even if you are rich, you sort of having difficulties earlier, you could go to an engineering college,

00:55:00.800 --> 00:55:02.840
[Guest]: probably go to the US now those things will not happen.

00:55:02.840 --> 00:55:06.440
[Guest]: You even if your father can afford 20 lakhs for a private engineering college, you will

00:55:06.440 --> 00:55:11.880
[Guest]: not get a job that easily, then ultimately, somebody has to go and build a political case

00:55:11.880 --> 00:55:14.200
[Guest]: that here is what needs to be done.

00:55:14.200 --> 00:55:19.360
[Guest]: I think, you know, this entire social media and no, I could sound a bit extremist when

00:55:19.360 --> 00:55:24.800
[Guest]: I say that is an alibi for a failure to come up with an effective opposition to the kind

00:55:24.800 --> 00:55:28.200
[Guest]: of right wing populism we are seeing, not just in our country, but in the world today.

00:55:28.200 --> 00:55:30.840
[Guest]: I mean, you cannot say that we'll go back to the past.

00:55:30.840 --> 00:55:34.840
[Guest]: So which is why probably a Hillary Clinton, you know, lost to Donald Trump.

00:55:34.840 --> 00:55:39.560
[Guest]: I mean, people associated certain kinds of things with Hillary Clinton, the old elite.

00:55:39.560 --> 00:55:44.600
