[Amit Varma]: Welcome back to the scene in the unseen.

00:59:04.080 --> 00:59:09.560
[Amit Varma]: I'm chatting with Roshan Kishore about data journalism, about the political economy, which

00:59:09.560 --> 00:59:10.560
[Amit Varma]: he writes about regularly.

00:59:10.560 --> 00:59:17.120
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, coming to sort of Indian politics now, you you've been a data journalism and

00:59:17.120 --> 00:59:22.720
[Amit Varma]: sort of a data journalist and sort of in the thick of things during what is a transformative

00:59:22.720 --> 00:59:25.520
[Amit Varma]: period in our politics.

00:59:25.520 --> 00:59:31.480
[Amit Varma]: Tell me a little bit about following politics during this time, you know, the 2014 elections,

00:59:31.480 --> 00:59:33.400
[Amit Varma]: the 2019 elections.

00:59:33.400 --> 00:59:34.400
[Amit Varma]: Has it?

00:59:34.400 --> 00:59:38.840
[Amit Varma]: Have there been parts of it which are bewildering, which have taken you by surprise?

00:59:38.840 --> 00:59:42.600
[Amit Varma]: And also how has a political, how has our politics changed during this time?

00:59:42.600 --> 00:59:48.440
[Guest]: So, ironical as it may sound, my most bewildering political experience actually doesn't come

00:59:48.440 --> 00:59:50.880
[Guest]: from doing data journalism, but going out in the field.

00:59:50.880 --> 00:59:54.000
[Guest]: This is during the Madhya Pradesh assembly elections.

00:59:54.000 --> 00:59:58.000
[Guest]: I think this was somewhere between Jabalpur and Bhopal district.

00:59:58.000 --> 01:00:02.160
[Guest]: We went to a village, talking to a bunch of people.

01:00:02.160 --> 01:00:04.080
[Guest]: All of these people were rooting for the Congress.

01:00:04.080 --> 01:00:07.960
[Guest]: They were extremely angry with the BJP government, etc.

01:00:07.960 --> 01:00:09.360
[Guest]: And we were having this conversation.

01:00:09.360 --> 01:00:14.040
[Guest]: And then this guy tells me that when the Babri mosque was being demolished, he along with

01:00:14.040 --> 01:00:18.080
[Guest]: all other villagers actually went to demolish it.

01:00:18.080 --> 01:00:24.400
[Guest]: So here is a group of voters who were not just supporters, but active participants in

01:00:24.400 --> 01:00:29.360
[Guest]: what is often and rightly thought of as one of the most communal acts of politics in our

01:00:29.360 --> 01:00:36.320
[Guest]: country organized then, but they were not voting for the party they were still aligned

01:00:36.320 --> 01:00:38.520
[Guest]: ideologically with.

01:00:38.520 --> 01:00:42.760
[Guest]: I think that is how complicated politics has become in our country.

01:00:42.760 --> 01:00:47.480
[Guest]: Or if I were to put it the other way, maybe politics has always been like that, but we

01:00:47.480 --> 01:00:50.560
[Guest]: never realized it was the way like that.

01:00:50.560 --> 01:00:55.440
[Guest]: So let us go back to the 2014 elections, Narendra Modi for the first time in 30 years got a

01:00:55.440 --> 01:00:58.880
[Guest]: majority on his own, made a big thing.

01:00:58.880 --> 01:01:03.840
[Guest]: A lot of explanation was that it is actually the anger against UPA2, you know, 2G and Commonwealth,

01:01:03.840 --> 01:01:05.840
[Guest]: etc, etc, etc.

01:01:05.840 --> 01:01:08.640
[Guest]: And then, you know, there was mixed evidence.

01:01:08.640 --> 01:01:13.680
[Guest]: So 2014, you win these elections, then you have some success in Maharashtra, Haryana,

01:01:13.680 --> 01:01:14.680
[Guest]: etc.

01:01:14.680 --> 01:01:19.000
[Guest]: And then we come to Delhi 2015, the BJP is all but wiped out, you get just three seats.

01:01:19.000 --> 01:01:23.360
[Guest]: Then no, you go to a completely different electoral battlefield, which is Bihar in 2015,

01:01:23.360 --> 01:01:24.360
[Guest]: October.

01:01:24.360 --> 01:01:31.360
[Guest]: Once again, somebody who's, who's been epitomized as the symbol of corruption, nepotism, etc,

01:01:31.360 --> 01:01:35.320
[Guest]: by the BJP, Lalu Prasad Yadav pulls off a spectacular victory along with Nitish Kumar

01:01:35.320 --> 01:01:37.120
[Guest]: with the BJP.

01:01:37.120 --> 01:01:42.440
[Guest]: Then you again, you know, 16, the BJP is irrelevant, because it's Bengal, Kerala, Assam, they win,

01:01:42.440 --> 01:01:45.600
[Guest]: but by and large, not major players.

01:01:45.600 --> 01:01:48.560
[Guest]: Then no demonetization happens, then UP happens.

01:01:48.560 --> 01:01:51.320
[Guest]: Then once again, there's a big bang, you know, the Bihar government falls under a bunch of

01:01:51.320 --> 01:01:55.320
[Guest]: its own contradictions, because the BJP, Nitish Kumar said it openly was invincible, nobody

01:01:55.320 --> 01:01:56.320
[Guest]: could defeat it.

01:01:56.320 --> 01:01:59.360
[Guest]: So he made it very, very clear why he was going.

01:01:59.360 --> 01:02:02.940
[Guest]: Then 17 onwards, we get into a completely different trajectory where the BJP manages

01:02:02.940 --> 01:02:07.360
[Guest]: to somehow retain Gujarat, then 18, there was the shock defeats for the BJP.

01:02:07.360 --> 01:02:12.280
[Guest]: So by the time we got to 2019, and I'm very honest about it, this was my personal belief

01:02:12.280 --> 01:02:14.840
[Guest]: as well that it was anything but a closed race.

01:02:14.840 --> 01:02:20.120
[Guest]: I mean, I did not see the BJP performing the way it did, because, you know, being a numbers

01:02:20.120 --> 01:02:22.160
[Guest]: guy was actually looking at those previous numbers.

01:02:22.160 --> 01:02:26.880
[Guest]: And if you look at previous assembly elections before 14, there was always 80% of the assembly

01:02:26.880 --> 01:02:30.060
[Guest]: elections actually sort of manifested in the Lok Sabha elections, the trends.

01:02:30.060 --> 01:02:36.200
[Guest]: So I thought there was no way the BJP could do what it ultimately ended up doing.

01:02:36.200 --> 01:02:40.640
[Guest]: Now that it has happened, I think one has to try and go back and ask those questions

01:02:40.640 --> 01:02:42.320
[Guest]: as to how it happened.

01:02:42.320 --> 01:02:47.240
[Guest]: Now, there are a bunch of people who think that EVMs are rigged, etc.

01:02:47.240 --> 01:02:48.240
[Guest]: I think all that is bogus.

01:02:48.240 --> 01:02:53.640
[Guest]: I mean, as simple as that, because, you know, the same sets of EVMs, etc. are being used.

01:02:53.640 --> 01:02:59.000
[Guest]: The biggest takeaway, I think, from the 19 victory of the BJP is that people in our country

01:02:59.000 --> 01:03:04.240
[Guest]: are actually voting separately at different levels of government formation.

01:03:04.240 --> 01:03:07.580
[Guest]: So they might elect somebody else to be the chief minister, they might elect somebody

01:03:07.580 --> 01:03:09.280
[Guest]: else to their prime minister.

01:03:09.280 --> 01:03:13.400
[Guest]: I mean, Odisha is a perfect example, it went to poll on the same day assembly and Lok

01:03:13.400 --> 01:03:16.320
[Guest]: Sabha elections have drastically different results.

01:03:16.320 --> 01:03:20.960
[Guest]: People voting in the same booth on the same day are voting for two different parties.

01:03:20.960 --> 01:03:25.400
[Guest]: Now this is, this is a very big thing as far as Indian democracy is concerned, Indian politics

01:03:25.400 --> 01:03:26.400
[Guest]: is concerned.

01:03:26.400 --> 01:03:31.820
[Guest]: This also means that the BJP going from here, no, however implausible it sounds right now,

01:03:31.820 --> 01:03:37.680
[Guest]: it sounded so in 2014, also might suffer reverses in state elections, but then the opposition

01:03:37.680 --> 01:03:42.720
[Guest]: because it will not have to not be able to construct a popular sort of narrative, along

01:03:42.720 --> 01:03:46.560
[Guest]: with a figure which is extremely important because now we are voting more for a leader

01:03:46.560 --> 01:03:50.240
[Guest]: rather than a party and the BJP also has absolutely no pretence in acknowledging that it is a

01:03:50.240 --> 01:03:52.280
[Guest]: vote for Narendra Modi.

01:03:52.280 --> 01:03:55.160
[Guest]: These are very interesting times.

01:03:55.160 --> 01:04:02.480
[Guest]: I think one has to have a substantive analysis of what Narendra Modi did.

01:04:02.480 --> 01:04:06.880
[Guest]: Now mind you, in politics, there could be things which we think are counterproductive

01:04:06.880 --> 01:04:10.160
[Guest]: something like demonetization, but could help politically.

01:04:10.160 --> 01:04:14.280
[Guest]: There are things, you know, such as demolition of the Babri mosque, which we think is very

01:04:14.280 --> 01:04:15.640
[Guest]: bad to do.

01:04:15.640 --> 01:04:19.880
[Guest]: But democracy, you know, we have to accept it is also a rule of the majority.

01:04:19.880 --> 01:04:24.040
[Guest]: So the majority of the people do not agree with an idea, however, right it is or agree

01:04:24.040 --> 01:04:28.080
[Guest]: with the idea, however, preposterous and dangerous it is, then that idea always sort of carries

01:04:28.080 --> 01:04:31.640
[Guest]: on in a democracy or we are a democracy.

01:04:31.640 --> 01:04:35.920
[Guest]: So we have to think along those lines, what are the things which they did right, which

01:04:35.920 --> 01:04:39.840
[Guest]: were also right for the larger interests of the country, the economy, the polity, which

01:04:39.840 --> 01:04:43.120
[Guest]: they did right, which were otherwise counterproductive.

01:04:43.120 --> 01:04:48.080
[Guest]: More importantly, what are the things which the opposition could not do, for example,

01:04:48.080 --> 01:04:49.080
[Guest]: something like demonetization.

01:04:49.080 --> 01:04:55.240
[Guest]: No, I still believe had the BJP been in opposition, the amount of public anger which would have

01:04:55.240 --> 01:04:59.320
[Guest]: erupted against demonetization, and you remember Venezuela tried something similar when demonetization

01:04:59.320 --> 01:05:05.620
[Guest]: exactly take it back, Venezuela is today a far more repressed democracy than India is.

01:05:05.620 --> 01:05:08.760
[Guest]: But India did not have one credible protest against demonetization.

01:05:08.760 --> 01:05:11.920
[Guest]: Now that speaks volumes about the failure of the opposition.

01:05:11.920 --> 01:05:15.960
[Guest]: Now the crudest explanation could be a lot of people, grassroots leaders were actually

01:05:15.960 --> 01:05:18.620
[Guest]: exchanging notes and you never know.

01:05:18.620 --> 01:05:24.880
[Guest]: But to be able to encash popular anger against, you know, a lot of policies which we think

01:05:24.880 --> 01:05:29.240
[Guest]: and some of which we rightly think are wrong, I think is also there also has to be an analysis

01:05:29.240 --> 01:05:31.600
[Guest]: of what was done by the opposition and what was not.

01:05:31.600 --> 01:05:37.400
[Guest]: So those are the two tracks in which I think any political analysis from now on must progress.

01:05:37.400 --> 01:05:42.760
[Amit Varma]: And if you sort of look at the broad currents along which people vote, you know, what really

01:05:42.760 --> 01:05:49.640
[Amit Varma]: happened around 89 and the 91 in that phase was that the two big issues that dominated

01:05:49.640 --> 01:05:53.280
[Amit Varma]: Indian politics became Mandal and Mandir and they completely changed Indian politics.

01:05:53.280 --> 01:05:57.680
[Amit Varma]: And you've written a recent piece called Mandal, Mandir and Markets where you talk about sort

01:05:57.680 --> 01:05:59.440
[Amit Varma]: of these three M's.

01:05:59.440 --> 01:06:02.740
[Amit Varma]: And I remember I think right after the election, I think it was Shekhar Gupta who wrote a piece

01:06:02.740 --> 01:06:07.720
[Amit Varma]: where he said that there's another M which has completely surpassed all these M's, which

01:06:07.720 --> 01:06:08.720
[Amit Varma]: is Modi.

01:06:08.720 --> 01:06:14.620
[Amit Varma]: And his point really was that Mandal and Mandir are now irrelevant.

01:06:14.620 --> 01:06:16.320
[Amit Varma]: This is a Modi thing.

01:06:16.320 --> 01:06:20.640
[Amit Varma]: And again, I believe there's some amount of data by Milan Vaishnava among others, which

01:06:20.640 --> 01:06:28.640
[Amit Varma]: backs up that a lot of people sort of, a lot less people would have voted for the BJP in

01:06:28.640 --> 01:06:34.240
[Amit Varma]: 2014, at least if Modi had not been the PM candidate.

01:06:34.240 --> 01:06:37.720
[Amit Varma]: How do you view this evolution of why people vote?

01:06:37.720 --> 01:06:42.360
[Amit Varma]: Are Mandal and Mandir and perhaps Markets still important reasons why people vote or

01:06:42.360 --> 01:06:44.400
[Amit Varma]: is it a very personality driven thing now?

01:06:44.400 --> 01:06:48.720
[Guest]: See, we were talking about it in the early part of the podcast, which is where you have

01:06:48.720 --> 01:06:55.720
[Guest]: to sort of realize how much to read into the data which you have now when surveys say that

01:06:55.720 --> 01:07:00.920
[Guest]: half of the people who voted for the BJP would probably not have voted for the BJP had Modi

01:07:00.920 --> 01:07:03.200
[Guest]: not been the prime ministerial candidate.

01:07:03.200 --> 01:07:06.400
[Guest]: We have to understand what is it that Modi brings to the BJP.

01:07:06.400 --> 01:07:09.080
[Guest]: I mean, it is not that people like his face and vote for him.

01:07:09.080 --> 01:07:10.640
[Guest]: I mean, it can't be.

01:07:10.640 --> 01:07:15.080
[Guest]: I think Narendra Modi today probably is the not only is the biggest mass leader in this

01:07:15.080 --> 01:07:20.640
[Guest]: country, he and under him the kind of BJP leadership which is developing.

01:07:20.640 --> 01:07:27.000
[Guest]: They are also people who are deeply convinced about what their core politics should be.

01:07:27.000 --> 01:07:31.560
[Guest]: So my generation, Narendra Modi is somebody now look at it from the BJP's point of view,

01:07:31.560 --> 01:07:35.240
[Guest]: say a core BJP voter driven by Hindutva, etc.

01:07:35.240 --> 01:07:39.680
[Guest]: Now, a lot of liberals actually try to turn 2002 against Narendra Modi.

01:07:39.680 --> 01:07:43.640
[Guest]: Now, Narendra Modi has never gone on the defensive with that.

01:07:43.640 --> 01:07:47.640
[Guest]: I think that plays a role in the psyche of the core BJP voter.

01:07:47.640 --> 01:07:49.160
[Amit Varma]: That's a feature, not a bug.

01:07:49.160 --> 01:07:52.760
[Guest]: He would never desert Narendra Modi because he stood the test of the time.

01:07:52.760 --> 01:07:56.400
[Guest]: He's not somebody like a Lalkrishna Adwani who went to Jinnah's mausoleum and did what

01:07:56.400 --> 01:07:57.400
[Guest]: he did.

01:07:57.400 --> 01:07:58.840
[Guest]: Similarly, there are a lot of other things.

01:07:58.840 --> 01:08:04.200
[Guest]: For example, you know, this entire thing, you know, we do not we did not have a 2002

01:08:04.200 --> 01:08:09.080
[Guest]: unlike before the 2004 elections, we did not even have 2003 Muzaffarnagar unlike what happened

01:08:09.080 --> 01:08:14.040
[Guest]: before the 2014 elections, which is what I've sort of argued in my Mandir Mandal Markets

01:08:14.040 --> 01:08:15.040
[Guest]: piece.

01:08:15.040 --> 01:08:19.640
[Guest]: Now, does that mean that there was no communal polarization before these elections?

01:08:19.640 --> 01:08:26.040
[Guest]: Look at things that what is happening in Kashmir today, you know, 370, 35A, these are matters

01:08:26.040 --> 01:08:27.760
[Guest]: of great detail.

01:08:27.760 --> 01:08:29.960
[Guest]: These are matters of constitutional integrity.

01:08:29.960 --> 01:08:32.160
[Guest]: What is the special status of Kashmir?

01:08:32.160 --> 01:08:36.160
[Guest]: If Kashmir does not have a constituent assembly, can you even remove these articles?

01:08:36.160 --> 01:08:40.860
[Guest]: If you were to do away with Article 370, will Kashmir technically be bound to be a part

01:08:40.860 --> 01:08:41.860
[Guest]: of India?

01:08:41.860 --> 01:08:44.160
[Guest]: We can debate ad nauseum about these things.

01:08:44.160 --> 01:08:51.000
[Guest]: But when a political party goes to a hinterland constituency in say, Eastern UP or Bihar,

01:08:51.000 --> 01:08:56.460
[Guest]: and poses this question that those who want 370 to stay are actually aiding and abetting

01:08:56.460 --> 01:09:01.160
[Guest]: the cause of separatists in Kashmir, I think it makes an extremely powerful impact on the

01:09:01.160 --> 01:09:02.160
[Guest]: voter.

01:09:02.160 --> 01:09:06.440
[Guest]: When you go out and say that, you know, we are bringing the citizenship amendment bill

01:09:06.440 --> 01:09:10.720
[Guest]: and all Hindus who are persecuted in say, Pakistan or Bangladesh or Afghanistan would

01:09:10.720 --> 01:09:15.720
[Guest]: be granted a citizenship of this country, I think you are making a very powerful point.

01:09:15.720 --> 01:09:20.560
[Guest]: Your core politics like it was in 2002, even today is intact.

01:09:20.560 --> 01:09:22.760
[Guest]: And I think the voter gets those messages.

01:09:22.760 --> 01:09:27.520
[Guest]: When you say that because Rahul Gandhi is contesting from Wayanad, which is a Muslim

01:09:27.520 --> 01:09:30.960
[Guest]: majority seat, it basically means that the Congress is only looking at Muslim votes in

01:09:30.960 --> 01:09:32.640
[Guest]: the 2019 elections.

01:09:32.640 --> 01:09:34.240
[Guest]: It makes a very powerful point.

01:09:34.240 --> 01:09:38.640
[Guest]: When the Prime Minister of India goes to a Gujarat election campaign and says that a

01:09:38.640 --> 01:09:44.560
[Guest]: former Prime Minister of India actually conspired with Pakistan to get him killed, you know,

01:09:44.560 --> 01:09:46.760
[Guest]: it's beyond the pale, but it strikes a chord.

01:09:46.760 --> 01:09:47.760
[Guest]: Yeah.

01:09:47.760 --> 01:09:54.960
[Guest]: So I think it is the BJP today has mastered the art of keeping the communal pot simmering

01:09:54.960 --> 01:09:58.720
[Guest]: without there being any large precipitation.

01:09:58.720 --> 01:10:01.960
[Guest]: They would not have a Muzaffarnagar on their hands, they will not have a Godhra, Gujarat,

01:10:01.960 --> 01:10:05.760
[Guest]: Ahmedabad, Naroda party on their hands, but the pot is still simmering.

01:10:05.760 --> 01:10:09.440
[Guest]: So if we were to go back to the social science analogy, the BJP has actually mastered the

01:10:09.440 --> 01:10:11.160
[Guest]: art of keeping the swimming pool empty.

01:10:11.160 --> 01:10:15.000
[Guest]: So the only people who jump in the swimming pool will be people of their own choosing.

01:10:15.000 --> 01:10:17.520
[Guest]: I think this has been a miserable failure of the opposition on that.

01:10:17.520 --> 01:10:21.320
[Guest]: And this is something I say from a lot of personal experience.

01:10:21.320 --> 01:10:26.440
[Guest]: I think it was in standard one when Lakhrishna Advani started a Ramshila Poojan Yatra, 89

01:10:26.440 --> 01:10:28.480
[Guest]: was when the Bhagarpur riots happened in Bihar.

01:10:28.480 --> 01:10:32.960
[Guest]: I mean, I remember our school was closed for a month because of communal tension.

01:10:32.960 --> 01:10:38.360
[Guest]: Since then, the Hindu right wing has never stopped its own propaganda.

01:10:38.360 --> 01:10:42.640
[Guest]: Sometimes it's Ayodhya, sometimes it will be Labh Jihad and right now it could be 370.

01:10:42.640 --> 01:10:45.280
[Guest]: They kept changing whatever suits them to do.

01:10:45.280 --> 01:10:50.720
[Guest]: The other side, on the other hand, always thought that the way to deal with it was not

01:10:50.720 --> 01:10:53.600
[Guest]: to take it head on, but sort of build bypasses around it.

01:10:53.600 --> 01:10:57.600
[Guest]: So in Bihar, Lalu Yadav built what is now famously referred to as an MY equation.

01:10:57.600 --> 01:11:00.640
[Guest]: I have the Muslims which are captive because anyway, they can't vote for the BJP.

01:11:00.640 --> 01:11:05.400
[Guest]: I'll get the Yadavs along and here in a first post the past system, I have this invincible

01:11:05.400 --> 01:11:10.080
[Guest]: target vote share level of say 36%, which is enough to beat everybody else.

01:11:10.080 --> 01:11:13.920
[Guest]: Narendra Modi and Amit Shah today are proving that that is not going to be enough because

01:11:13.920 --> 01:11:17.120
[Guest]: we'll surpass 50% in each and every state.

01:11:17.120 --> 01:11:20.240
[Guest]: That is the next level they've taken in the politics.

01:11:20.240 --> 01:11:27.040
[Guest]: So I think it is extremely important to realize what the success of the present leadership

01:11:27.040 --> 01:11:28.160
[Amit Varma]: of the BJP is.

01:11:28.160 --> 01:11:33.040
[Amit Varma]: And it also seems to me that there's an apparent contradiction there which bewilders me.

01:11:33.040 --> 01:11:36.960
[Amit Varma]: So on one hand, I completely agree with you that a lot of the support for Modi is not

01:11:36.960 --> 01:11:41.800
[Amit Varma]: necessarily because of his personality and all of that, but because he stands for a vision

01:11:41.800 --> 01:11:44.520
[Amit Varma]: and an ideology which people feel deeply.

01:11:44.520 --> 01:11:51.400
[Amit Varma]: But also it is true that just as the BJP has an ideological purity, which no other party

01:11:51.400 --> 01:11:55.840
[Amit Varma]: has because other parties don't really stand for something which is as powerful within

01:11:55.840 --> 01:12:01.280
[Amit Varma]: Indian culture, but also a parallel strand of the BJP political movement in the last

01:12:01.280 --> 01:12:07.560
[Amit Varma]: few years has been a will to power perhaps, you know, led by the political strategy of

01:12:07.560 --> 01:12:12.240
[Amit Varma]: Amit Shah, where he almost does a mergers and acquisitions things where you're always

01:12:12.240 --> 01:12:15.320
[Amit Varma]: constantly acquiring people from other parties, right?

01:12:15.320 --> 01:12:19.600
[Amit Varma]: So you'll go to the Northeast and you'll acquire people and Gujarat elections or Goa elections,

01:12:19.600 --> 01:12:23.240
[Amit Varma]: whatever happens, you'll acquire some people and you'll do whatever.

01:12:23.240 --> 01:12:27.480
[Amit Varma]: And that seems almost contradictory to this because on the one hand, you stand for ideological

01:12:27.480 --> 01:12:28.480
[Amit Varma]: purity.

01:12:28.480 --> 01:12:32.240
[Amit Varma]: But on the other hand, you're bringing in people you opposed and who opposed you very

01:12:32.240 --> 01:12:34.840
[Amit Varma]: strongly into your fold.

01:12:34.840 --> 01:12:38.880
[Amit Varma]: And almost like saying that, okay, we'll be this broad umbrella, you know, and it's been

01:12:38.880 --> 01:12:43.600
[Amit Varma]: very successful for them both in terms of bringing other politicians into the party

01:12:43.600 --> 01:12:48.640
[Amit Varma]: and managing to form governments and so on and decimating the opposition.

01:12:48.640 --> 01:12:53.720
[Amit Varma]: It's also that broadening of their typical social base has also been successful in terms

01:12:53.720 --> 01:12:59.480
[Amit Varma]: of, you know, for example, famously getting non-Yadav OBCs in UP, non-Jatav Dalits and

01:12:59.480 --> 01:13:03.080
[Amit Varma]: in fact, they now, you know, in both elections, they've had a larger share of the Dalit vote

01:13:03.080 --> 01:13:05.360
[Amit Varma]: than the Congress has.

01:13:05.360 --> 01:13:09.080
[Amit Varma]: Is there a sort of a contradiction here that on one hand, it stands for this firm kind

01:13:09.080 --> 01:13:12.640
[Amit Varma]: of ideological purity and on the other hand, it's just taking in everybody?

01:13:12.640 --> 01:13:16.800
[Guest]: I'll go back to my earlier avatar as a political activist and not a journalist.

01:13:16.800 --> 01:13:19.840
[Guest]: I think this is what politics is.

01:13:19.840 --> 01:13:24.600
[Guest]: Day to day politics, especially in a country which is as diverse as India and as big as

01:13:24.600 --> 01:13:30.960
[Guest]: India, it can never be adhering to a text cast in stone.

01:13:30.960 --> 01:13:36.360
[Guest]: Politics in India always has to be about and it will be about handling contradictions.

01:13:36.360 --> 01:13:39.800
[Guest]: So if the BJP can handle its contradictions in Goa, it'll have a field run.

01:13:39.800 --> 01:13:43.520
[Guest]: The BJP could not handle its contradiction in Kashmir, so the government fell.

01:13:43.520 --> 01:13:49.760
[Guest]: I think politicians, and this is where persons become important, because sometimes, you know,

01:13:49.760 --> 01:13:51.760
[Guest]: it could depend on just one person.

01:13:51.760 --> 01:13:55.160
[Guest]: So it took an Atal Bihari Vajpayee to run an NDA coalition for that.

01:13:55.160 --> 01:13:58.640
[Guest]: I think if the BJP today had those kinds of numbers, nobody would do business with Narendra

01:13:58.640 --> 01:13:59.640
[Guest]: Modi.

01:13:59.640 --> 01:14:03.520
[Guest]: It is only because Narendra Modi has the majority that people know, JDU with all their reservations,

01:14:03.520 --> 01:14:06.280
[Guest]: I don't know how they're going to vote on the triple talaq bill today, but they'll stay

01:14:06.280 --> 01:14:07.280
[Guest]: with the NDA.

01:14:07.280 --> 01:14:13.200
[Amit Varma]: So I think that is where the art of handling contradictions

01:14:13.200 --> 01:14:15.080
[Guest]: becomes extremely important.

01:14:15.080 --> 01:14:18.680
[Guest]: And that is where the rest of the opposition has absolutely no idea what to do.

01:14:18.680 --> 01:14:23.840
[Guest]: I mean, look at Bihar, for example, now, I'm from JNU, so I have a bias.

01:14:23.840 --> 01:14:26.820
[Guest]: So Kanhaiya went and contested Begusarai.

01:14:26.820 --> 01:14:30.120
[Guest]: He actually came second, whereas the RJD candidate came third.

01:14:30.120 --> 01:14:32.840
[Guest]: But Tejasvi Yadav, you know, he was in charge of things.

01:14:32.840 --> 01:14:35.760
[Guest]: He could not even give that one Lok Sabha seat to Kanhaiya.

01:14:35.760 --> 01:14:36.760
[Guest]: Look at the BJP.

01:14:36.760 --> 01:14:40.520
[Guest]: I mean, it gave an equal number of seats to the Janata Dal United.

01:14:40.520 --> 01:14:43.240
[Guest]: Now we all know that the BJP did not need to do that.

01:14:43.240 --> 01:14:44.840
[Guest]: Look at what they've done to the Shiv Sena.

01:14:44.840 --> 01:14:48.480
[Guest]: Amit Shah went to Uddhav Thackeray's house to sort of accommodate, placate Uddhav Thackeray.

01:14:48.480 --> 01:14:50.320
[Guest]: No, no, you have to stay with us.

01:14:50.320 --> 01:14:54.600
[Guest]: I think this is something, you know, you might think that the BJP leadership, you know, a

01:14:54.600 --> 01:14:58.320
[Guest]: lot of people say that, you know, they are all fundamentalist and very, you know, sort

01:14:58.320 --> 01:15:00.320
[Guest]: of predatory in nature, etc.

01:15:00.320 --> 01:15:04.960
[Guest]: But I think behind this so-called strong face of the BJP leadership, which people like Narendra

01:15:04.960 --> 01:15:10.240
[Guest]: Modi and Amit Shah sort of display, I think they also bring with them a lot of flexibility

01:15:10.240 --> 01:15:15.680
[Guest]: in day-to-day politics, a lot of commitment to protect their core ideology, even while

01:15:15.680 --> 01:15:17.160
[Guest]: doing all these compromises.

01:15:17.160 --> 01:15:21.160
[Guest]: And a lot of the electoral success with the BJP has had in this country in the recent

01:15:21.160 --> 01:15:22.560
[Guest]: past is also because of that.

01:15:22.560 --> 01:15:24.080
[Guest]: It is not just ideology.

01:15:24.080 --> 01:15:28.520
[Guest]: They are doing, you know, the BJP might oppose beef-eating in say, Uttar Pradesh or Bihar,

01:15:28.520 --> 01:15:31.160
[Guest]: but they would go to the Northeast and say that you please go ahead, eat your beef, we

01:15:31.160 --> 01:15:32.320
[Guest]: have absolutely no problems with you.

01:15:32.320 --> 01:15:34.200
[Guest]: They are doing business with the Christians in Kerala.

01:15:34.200 --> 01:15:37.600
[Guest]: They made a minister who comes from the Christian community in the state, they have absolutely

01:15:37.600 --> 01:15:38.600
[Guest]: no problems with beef-eating.

01:15:38.600 --> 01:15:43.840
[Guest]: So the BJP today is not only the most ideologically convinced party in this country, it is also

01:15:43.840 --> 01:15:49.800
[Guest]: the most flexible and pragmatic party in the country when it comes to political praxis.

01:15:49.800 --> 01:15:54.680
[Amit Varma]: So let's say it practices all this flexible politics as a means to an end, which is to

01:15:54.680 --> 01:15:55.880
[Amit Varma]: come to power.

01:15:55.880 --> 01:16:02.000
[Amit Varma]: But when it comes to power, its core supporters would expect it to carry, to do something

01:16:02.000 --> 01:16:06.280
[Amit Varma]: about their ideology, whether it's Mandir Banao or Bank House Rotter or Build a Hindu

01:16:06.280 --> 01:16:07.280
[Amit Varma]: Rashtra.

01:16:07.280 --> 01:16:08.920
[Amit Varma]: So where do you sort of see it going?

01:16:08.920 --> 01:16:09.920
[Amit Varma]: Like what is the future?

01:16:09.920 --> 01:16:14.240
[Amit Varma]: Do you just keep the circle going where, you know, your means to an end is again, coming

01:16:14.240 --> 01:16:15.700
[Amit Varma]: to power is an end in itself?

01:16:15.700 --> 01:16:17.760
[Amit Varma]: Is that where it continues going?

01:16:17.760 --> 01:16:22.320
[Amit Varma]: Or does it actually start acting upon some of this and we go in those without casting

01:16:22.320 --> 01:16:26.360
[Amit Varma]: a value judgment on those directions, like, forget whether Hindu Rashtra is desirable

01:16:26.360 --> 01:16:28.920
[Amit Varma]: or not, or whether we should build a temple or not.

01:16:28.920 --> 01:16:31.640
[Guest]: But so there are two ways about it.

01:16:31.640 --> 01:16:37.360
[Guest]: One is, you know, people who are more Christian than the Pope within the BJP ranks, if you

01:16:37.360 --> 01:16:41.960
[Guest]: want to use that phrase, what do they do when the government doesn't deliver?

01:16:41.960 --> 01:16:47.160
[Guest]: Now, they either have a choice of going and floating something which is, you know, even

01:16:47.160 --> 01:16:51.200
[Guest]: to the right of say the BJP, or they have the choice of going and doing business with

01:16:51.200 --> 01:16:52.200
[Guest]: the opposition.

01:16:52.200 --> 01:16:56.880
[Guest]: So like I said, you know, the Babri Masjid, the farmer angry with the BJP example, I think

01:16:56.880 --> 01:16:58.520
[Guest]: both of these cases happen.

01:16:58.520 --> 01:17:02.560
[Guest]: So we have that farmer in Madhya Pradesh, who actually went and took part in demolishing

01:17:02.560 --> 01:17:04.760
[Guest]: the Babri Mosque, but voted for the Congress.

01:17:04.760 --> 01:17:08.640
[Guest]: We have somebody like a Praveen Togadia, who my generation has always associated as the

01:17:08.640 --> 01:17:12.280
[Guest]: most rabid right wing political voice in the country, who actually has been who was trying

01:17:12.280 --> 01:17:15.800
[Guest]: to criticize Modi and sort of cause some political damage, none of it happened.

01:17:15.800 --> 01:17:18.880
[Amit Varma]: And back when Modi was CM of Gujarat, he had actually sidelined Togadia.

01:17:18.880 --> 01:17:19.880
[Guest]: Yeah.

01:17:19.880 --> 01:17:22.840
[Guest]: So I think both of these trends will continue.

01:17:22.840 --> 01:17:28.080
[Guest]: But what I think is how it works is a large part of that political spectrum, which actually

01:17:28.080 --> 01:17:33.240
[Guest]: concurs with the worldview of the BJP today, also thinks that if this government were not

01:17:33.240 --> 01:17:36.000
[Guest]: to be in power, they would actually be worse off.

01:17:36.000 --> 01:17:39.680
[Guest]: So with all the reservations, which they might have, they actually think that it is in their

01:17:39.680 --> 01:17:42.640
[Guest]: interest to sort of continue investing in this regime.

01:17:42.640 --> 01:17:43.640
[Amit Varma]: Right.

01:17:43.640 --> 01:17:48.040
[Amit Varma]: And let's kind of move on from the BJP to the opposition.

01:17:48.040 --> 01:17:53.640
[Amit Varma]: And you recently wrote a piece about how Rahul Gandhi's analysis of why they lost the elections

01:17:53.640 --> 01:17:54.640
[Amit Varma]: is completely wrong.

01:17:54.640 --> 01:17:57.360
[Amit Varma]: Can you elaborate on that a bit?

01:17:57.360 --> 01:18:02.720
[Guest]: So if one were to very crudely summarize Rahul Gandhi's letter, it basically meant that the

01:18:02.720 --> 01:18:06.360
[Guest]: Congress should be doing more of what it was already doing.

01:18:06.360 --> 01:18:07.920
[Guest]: I don't think that helps.

01:18:07.920 --> 01:18:12.100
[Guest]: No, the biggest reason it doesn't help is because the Congress actually won those three

01:18:12.100 --> 01:18:16.840
[Guest]: states, you know, in December 2018, and in less than six months, it ended up losing all

01:18:16.840 --> 01:18:17.840
[Guest]: of them.

01:18:17.840 --> 01:18:21.280
[Guest]: So it can't just be organization in my view, it can't be the case that your activists were

01:18:21.280 --> 01:18:25.220
[Guest]: actually delivering six months ago, and today they can't.

01:18:25.220 --> 01:18:27.880
[Guest]: The question is, what do you do about it?

01:18:27.880 --> 01:18:33.880
[Guest]: I think one part of it is you have absolutely no idea how to build a constructive effective

01:18:33.880 --> 01:18:36.980
[Guest]: critique of this government's economic limitations.

01:18:36.980 --> 01:18:39.360
[Guest]: And there are many, I personally believe that.

01:18:39.360 --> 01:18:42.060
[Guest]: So you actually do not know what to go and talk to whom.

01:18:42.060 --> 01:18:45.880
[Guest]: The second thing is, I think the Congress and which is where I focus a large part of

01:18:45.880 --> 01:18:50.600
[Guest]: my piece on is the Congress has no idea how to take care of this Hindu polarization business.

01:18:50.600 --> 01:18:55.080
[Guest]: They actually want to be seen as Hindus, which reflects in the temple visits and whatnot

01:18:55.080 --> 01:19:00.120
[Guest]: done by especially the two active politicians from the Gandhi family, Rahul Gandhi and Priyanka

01:19:00.120 --> 01:19:06.360
[Guest]: in these elections and before these elections, but they don't know how they should be doing

01:19:06.360 --> 01:19:07.360
[Guest]: it.

01:19:07.360 --> 01:19:12.800
[Guest]: Because like I argued in this piece, it is not enough for you if you want to counter

01:19:12.800 --> 01:19:16.520
[Guest]: the BJP politically to be seen as pro-Hindu.

01:19:16.520 --> 01:19:21.420
[Guest]: There would be moments in the campaign in before an election where the BJP would actually

01:19:21.420 --> 01:19:28.600
[Guest]: portray itself as either explicitly or not so explicitly anti-Muslim.

01:19:28.600 --> 01:19:32.960
[Guest]: So when you say you would implement NRC in the entire country, I mean, people understand

01:19:32.960 --> 01:19:34.040
[Guest]: what you're hinting at.

01:19:34.040 --> 01:19:37.480
[Guest]: You basically hinting at the fact that there are a lot of Bangladeshi Muslims in this country

01:19:37.480 --> 01:19:40.600
[Guest]: who could actually be West Bengali Muslims and you would deport them.

01:19:40.600 --> 01:19:43.600
[Guest]: He would never come to do around to doing that.

01:19:43.600 --> 01:19:46.920
[Guest]: But this is something nobody in the opposition can go and champion.

01:19:46.920 --> 01:19:52.200
[Guest]: When Narendra Modi goes to say Calcutta and says that Mamata Banerjee is preventing us

01:19:52.200 --> 01:19:56.600
[Guest]: from implementing NRC here and she's Farooq Abdullah's ally who is preventing us from

01:19:56.600 --> 01:20:01.160
[Guest]: abolishing Article 370 there, which basically helps terrorists, etc.

01:20:01.160 --> 01:20:06.880
[Guest]: How does the opposition go and deal with this acquisition by the BJP?

01:20:06.880 --> 01:20:12.000
[Guest]: Now can you go to an average villager in say Begusara in Bihar or Gorakhpur in Uttar Pradesh

01:20:12.000 --> 01:20:17.160
[Guest]: and teach him or her what was the instrument of accession when Kashmir was being annexed

01:20:17.160 --> 01:20:18.400
[Guest]: to our country?

01:20:18.400 --> 01:20:23.200
[Guest]: What happens if article, no, or do you go to people around the country and show them

01:20:23.200 --> 01:20:26.920
[Guest]: census data that this is what Bangladeshi infiltration is, this is what the number of

01:20:26.920 --> 01:20:30.280
[Guest]: Bengali speakers in a lot of places is, doesn't work like that.

01:20:30.280 --> 01:20:35.800
[Guest]: I think, and this is where, you know, cultural intervention becomes very important.

01:20:35.800 --> 01:20:41.280
[Guest]: This day-to-day primacy of the unidirectional cultural discourse, which has happened in

01:20:41.280 --> 01:20:45.280
[Guest]: our country, which the right wing, especially the, you know, which is sort of in concurrence

01:20:45.280 --> 01:20:49.360
[Guest]: with the politics of the BJP has completely, I think, occupied.

01:20:49.360 --> 01:20:50.360
[Guest]: How do you deal with it?

01:20:50.360 --> 01:20:54.800
[Guest]: There's absolutely no, there's been no effort by the opposition to take it.

01:20:54.800 --> 01:20:59.160
[Guest]: Now one part of it can be economic, you know, that actually, you know, religion is the opium

01:20:59.160 --> 01:21:00.720
[Guest]: of the masses and you don't have the job.

01:21:00.720 --> 01:21:05.880
[Guest]: So basically all this is being sent to, but I think in a country like India, you know,

01:21:05.880 --> 01:21:10.760
[Guest]: so this is something Walter Anderson's book on the RSS when it was released, I was invited

01:21:10.760 --> 01:21:14.160
[Guest]: to a discussion on the book where Professor Anderson himself was present.

01:21:14.160 --> 01:21:19.980
[Guest]: So this is something I said there that actually, you know, a lot of intellectuals in India

01:21:19.980 --> 01:21:27.040
[Guest]: criticize the RSS on the basis of the premise that RSS's worldview does not stand intellectual

01:21:27.040 --> 01:21:28.040
[Guest]: scrutiny.

01:21:28.040 --> 01:21:33.480
[Guest]: We have to understand that the RSS is not an intellectual institution.

01:21:33.480 --> 01:21:38.440
[Guest]: It does not require intellectual scrutiny and sanctity to sort of propagate its ideas.

01:21:38.440 --> 01:21:43.400
[Guest]: It is at the end of the day, a majoritarian religious body, which basically needs to consolidate

01:21:43.400 --> 01:21:45.680
[Guest]: people from its old religion.

01:21:45.680 --> 01:21:47.400
[Guest]: And I said, look at somebody like Mahatma Gandhi.

01:21:47.400 --> 01:21:54.400
[Guest]: I mean, if you were to intellectually analyze Mahatma Gandhi, I mean, any rational intellectual

01:21:54.400 --> 01:21:58.480
[Guest]: would find a 1000 problems with the kind of arguments, political praxis, behavior he indulged

01:21:58.480 --> 01:22:02.000
[Guest]: in, right from his Gram Swaraj to many other things.

01:22:02.000 --> 01:22:04.600
[Guest]: But he was the biggest mass leader in our country.

01:22:04.600 --> 01:22:09.480
[Guest]: So politics and rationality are two sets where there is a significant union, but not all

01:22:09.480 --> 01:22:10.480
[Guest]: of it is common.

01:22:10.480 --> 01:22:14.360
[Guest]: I think the opposition, especially the Congress Party needs to figure out how do you deal

01:22:14.360 --> 01:22:19.520
[Guest]: with this, you know, dog whistling, if one could use the term against Muslims in day

01:22:19.520 --> 01:22:24.440
[Guest]: to day politics by the BJP, especially during elections, what do you do about it?

01:22:24.440 --> 01:22:27.960
[Guest]: Unless they have an answer to this question, which I'm pretty sure they do not have because

01:22:27.960 --> 01:22:31.120
[Guest]: the only thing they could figure out was going to temples, they are going to have a very

01:22:31.120 --> 01:22:33.480
[Amit Varma]: difficult time in dealing with the BJP.

01:22:33.480 --> 01:22:36.020
[Amit Varma]: And what you just said a couple of thoughts strike me about the Congress.

01:22:36.020 --> 01:22:41.040
[Amit Varma]: One is that if you go back to the history of the Congress, you'll find that pre independence

01:22:41.040 --> 01:22:46.240
[Amit Varma]: and even for a few years after independence, a Congress within it had genuine Hindu nationalist

01:22:46.240 --> 01:22:47.680
[Amit Varma]: leaders of nature.

01:22:47.680 --> 01:22:51.280
[Amit Varma]: Madan Mohan Malviya founded Banaras Hindu University.

01:22:51.280 --> 01:22:54.960
[Amit Varma]: And at the time, you know, you had at the time of independence, Sardar Patel was there,

01:22:54.960 --> 01:22:59.720
[Amit Varma]: Govind Vallabh Pant was the CM of UP, Lal Bahadur Shastri was a Home Minister of UP.

01:22:59.720 --> 01:23:03.200
[Amit Varma]: In fact, both of them were in charge when the Ram Idol was installed in Ayodhya.

01:23:03.200 --> 01:23:07.960
[Amit Varma]: And I think 49 and Nehru said remove it and they obfuscated and they denied it.

01:23:07.960 --> 01:23:11.840
[Amit Varma]: So you had these Hindu nationalist leaders whom Hindus could take seriously.

01:23:11.840 --> 01:23:16.400
[Amit Varma]: Today, there are no leaders like that within the Congress for good or for bad and all of

01:23:16.400 --> 01:23:21.740
[Amit Varma]: what they do like Rahul Gandhi going to Kedarnath is frankly just very obvious posturing.

01:23:21.740 --> 01:23:24.600
[Amit Varma]: You can only sort of just laugh at that.

01:23:24.600 --> 01:23:29.000
[Amit Varma]: And I totally agree with what you also earlier said about how you cannot hug back to the

01:23:29.000 --> 01:23:33.800
[Amit Varma]: politics like one point that I keep making about the Congress and the BJP, the contrast

01:23:33.800 --> 01:23:40.240
[Amit Varma]: between them and this is actually a criticism of both in a sense, is that the Congress behaves

01:23:40.240 --> 01:23:42.600
[Amit Varma]: as if history began in 2014.

01:23:42.600 --> 01:23:47.120
[Amit Varma]: So they will constantly talk about all that has gone wrong since 2014 and a lot has so

01:23:47.120 --> 01:23:49.480
[Amit Varma]: all of that criticism is completely valid.

01:23:49.480 --> 01:23:51.920
[Amit Varma]: But they will ignore their own sins of the past.

01:23:51.920 --> 01:23:57.120
[Amit Varma]: And they will ignore that voters have turned to Modi and rejected them because of the misgovernance

01:23:57.120 --> 01:24:02.840
[Amit Varma]: of decades and you know, not only will they not engage with that, they will promise the

01:24:02.840 --> 01:24:07.160
[Amit Varma]: same kind of policies and the same kind of visions for the future, which has already

01:24:07.160 --> 01:24:10.680
[Amit Varma]: and correctly, in my view, been rejected by the nation.

01:24:10.680 --> 01:24:14.920
[Amit Varma]: And the BJP is a converse of that where they behave as if history ended at 2014.

01:24:14.920 --> 01:24:17.680
[Amit Varma]: So what Modi did in the last five years is irrelevant.

01:24:17.680 --> 01:24:18.680
[Guest]: Everything is Nehru's fault.

01:24:18.680 --> 01:24:23.200
[Guest]: No, I would actually you know, I was like, I think it is a Congress which believes that

01:24:23.200 --> 01:24:24.200
[Guest]: history.

01:24:24.200 --> 01:24:28.400
[Guest]: I think that the Congress actually thinks that we are still not in 2014.

01:24:28.400 --> 01:24:29.400
[Guest]: Okay, we haven't.

01:24:29.400 --> 01:24:33.520
[Guest]: They have a sense of political entitlement, which I think makes them think that the Congress

01:24:33.520 --> 01:24:38.280
[Guest]: still should be the default choice of the people in this country.

01:24:38.280 --> 01:24:42.680
[Guest]: Now, 14, there was a question whether it was a one off thing or not.

01:24:42.680 --> 01:24:47.180
[Guest]: But I think between 14 and 19, now we know that that is not going to be the case.

01:24:47.180 --> 01:24:51.280
[Guest]: So the Congress Party has to realize that and if the Congress Party actually wants to

01:24:51.280 --> 01:24:55.520
[Guest]: regain its stature as the default political choice of the people in our country, it has

01:24:55.520 --> 01:24:59.480
[Guest]: to completely reinvent not just its organization, but also its politics.

01:24:59.480 --> 01:25:04.640
[Guest]: So there was a phase in Indian politics which lasted, you know, one could say from Nehru

01:25:04.640 --> 01:25:08.920
[Guest]: till the emergency was one phase, then post emergency was a very turbulent phase.

01:25:08.920 --> 01:25:12.600
[Guest]: Then we had this relative degree of stability, I think post 14, we have entered into a completely

01:25:12.600 --> 01:25:15.480
[Amit Varma]: new phase, the Congress has to realize that.

01:25:15.480 --> 01:25:18.600
[Amit Varma]: And is there a way out of it for them?

01:25:18.600 --> 01:25:22.160
[Amit Varma]: Both in terms of realistically, is there a way out of it given what the organization

01:25:22.160 --> 01:25:27.780
[Amit Varma]: is today, and and the near feudal capture and the erosion of the organization itself?

01:25:27.780 --> 01:25:30.720
[Amit Varma]: And also that if they is there a way out of it?

01:25:30.720 --> 01:25:34.640
[Amit Varma]: Is there a potential hypothetical way out of it just in terms of narrative?

01:25:34.640 --> 01:25:38.920
[Amit Varma]: Because the question that you yourself asked, how do you counter this dominant narrative?

01:25:38.920 --> 01:25:43.760
[Amit Varma]: It's obviously not by you know, going harking back to the past, but then how?

01:25:43.760 --> 01:25:45.480
[Guest]: I think it's a two step problem.

01:25:45.480 --> 01:25:48.840
[Guest]: Now, let us go back to the example of Narendra Modi.

01:25:48.840 --> 01:25:53.680
[Guest]: Narendra Modi comes from an extremely ordinary family in this country.

01:25:53.680 --> 01:25:59.920
[Guest]: The kind of political choices he made when he made them to become a swamsevak, I mean,

01:25:59.920 --> 01:26:03.240
[Guest]: despite being married, not have a family life, etc.

01:26:03.240 --> 01:26:07.360
[Guest]: I think even in his wildest dreams, he would never have imagined that he would end up being

01:26:07.360 --> 01:26:09.080
[Guest]: where he is today.

01:26:09.080 --> 01:26:11.920
[Guest]: You have to give it to him.

01:26:11.920 --> 01:26:13.920
[Guest]: Let us come back to the Congress now.

01:26:13.920 --> 01:26:19.840
[Guest]: An average Congress person, you know, who's entrained in the leadership, say, if we were

01:26:19.840 --> 01:26:25.320
[Guest]: to look at top 20,000 people in the Congress organization in this country, if they were

01:26:25.320 --> 01:26:30.980
[Guest]: asked to explain, why is it politically that they are with the Congress Party?

01:26:30.980 --> 01:26:34.640
[Guest]: And if you were to exclude say religious minorities in our country, because they have a vested

01:26:34.640 --> 01:26:39.280
[Guest]: interest in promoting a political force, which is by and large secular in its outlook.

01:26:39.280 --> 01:26:42.960
[Guest]: Now, the Congress has made those compromises with secularism, but we know that they are

01:26:42.960 --> 01:26:46.360
[Guest]: programmatically completely different from what the BJP is.

01:26:46.360 --> 01:26:50.600
[Guest]: If you were to ask those 10,000 people who come from the majority religious community

01:26:50.600 --> 01:26:53.560
[Guest]: Hindus in this country, why are you in the Congress Party?

01:26:53.560 --> 01:26:57.680
[Guest]: I think all of them would struggle very hard to come up with a coherent answer.

01:26:57.680 --> 01:26:59.040
[Guest]: That would not be the case.

01:26:59.040 --> 01:27:03.960
[Guest]: I would not say it so much about the BJP, but at least with the RSS in this country.

01:27:03.960 --> 01:27:07.660
[Guest]: I mean, you might disagree with their worldview or agree with it, but they will tell you exactly

01:27:07.660 --> 01:27:11.720
[Guest]: why they are in the RSS and why they would be in the RSS, why they would sort of get

01:27:11.720 --> 01:27:12.720
[Guest]: people.

01:27:12.720 --> 01:27:13.720
[Guest]: So that is the basic problem.

01:27:13.720 --> 01:27:18.880
[Guest]: I think, I mean, you have to have, now there is that material basis, if you want to enter

01:27:18.880 --> 01:27:21.880
[Guest]: into politics, you do some real estate, you get some more money here.

01:27:21.880 --> 01:27:26.240
[Guest]: That is how we know local politics, that is how it operates in the entire country today.

01:27:26.240 --> 01:27:29.760
[Guest]: The scale might differ depending on how developed your capitalism is.

01:27:29.760 --> 01:27:34.600
[Guest]: But the subjective question regarding politics, I think, and this is a crisis not just of

01:27:34.600 --> 01:27:37.480
[Guest]: the Congress, but also of the left today in our country.

01:27:37.480 --> 01:27:42.760
[Guest]: I mean, if you were to go to JNU, recruit somebody, say, you know, become a part of

01:27:42.760 --> 01:27:43.760
[Guest]: the SFI.

01:27:43.760 --> 01:27:44.760
[Guest]: Why?

01:27:44.760 --> 01:27:45.760
[Guest]: I mean, there's not going to be a revolution.

01:27:45.760 --> 01:27:48.520
[Guest]: I don't think any communist leader in this country believes that there's going to be

01:27:48.520 --> 01:27:49.520
[Guest]: a revolution in the world.

01:27:49.520 --> 01:27:54.320
[Guest]: I mean, you used to have a government in West Bengal, which notwithstanding all its problems

01:27:54.320 --> 01:27:58.080
[Guest]: had a very glorious track record in terms of basic land distribution, etc.

01:27:58.080 --> 01:27:59.920
[Guest]: That doesn't hold today.

01:27:59.920 --> 01:28:01.560
[Guest]: So why should I join the left?

01:28:01.560 --> 01:28:06.080
[Guest]: I mean, in your party program, you still say that North Korea is a socialist country, you

01:28:06.080 --> 01:28:10.320
[Guest]: still say that China is a socialist country today, you know, despite of all the problems

01:28:10.320 --> 01:28:14.680
[Guest]: which are happening in Venezuela, and I think Chavez did some good things and certain things

01:28:14.680 --> 01:28:16.540
[Guest]: have came back to bite the regime.

01:28:16.540 --> 01:28:22.940
[Guest]: But you if you continue to celebrate those things, then where do you draw the moral grandstanding

01:28:22.940 --> 01:28:29.360
[Guest]: from to be able to attract bright intellectual people into your folds, who would then be

01:28:29.360 --> 01:28:33.880
[Guest]: willing to make a certain amount of individual sacrifice to sort of further your political

01:28:33.880 --> 01:28:37.920
[Guest]: cause because Narendra Modi made a certain amount of political sacrifice very early in

01:28:37.920 --> 01:28:38.920
[Guest]: his political career.

01:28:38.920 --> 01:28:42.280
[Guest]: Amit Shah comes from a very wealthy businessman family.

01:28:42.280 --> 01:28:45.960
[Guest]: So I think, you know, we might have a lot of disagreements with him, but he made a certain

01:28:45.960 --> 01:28:50.600
[Guest]: amount of political sacrifice to give time and resources to the BJP.

01:28:50.600 --> 01:28:54.120
[Guest]: And that was the case the entire generation, the socialist leadership of this country from

01:28:54.120 --> 01:28:58.640
[Guest]: Nitish Kumar to Lalu Yadav to everybody else, all of them made political sacrifices during

01:28:58.640 --> 01:29:03.640
[Guest]: the anti-emergency struggle, they were put in jail, they faced a lot of state atrocity.

01:29:03.640 --> 01:29:09.920
[Guest]: Now, all of those acts, I do not think can be, you know, a product of purely Machiavellian

01:29:09.920 --> 01:29:12.400
[Guest]: consideration that I have to do well in politics, hence I have to do that.

01:29:12.400 --> 01:29:14.580
[Guest]: I don't think that is the case.

01:29:14.580 --> 01:29:18.960
[Guest]: So there was a degree of romanticism, subjectivism, etc.

01:29:18.960 --> 01:29:23.200
[Guest]: As far as the larger thing is concerned, and this is far more difficult here, because a

01:29:23.200 --> 01:29:26.480
[Guest]: with no liberalization, etc.

01:29:26.480 --> 01:29:30.220
[Guest]: People who study in elite institutions, I think people like us have a lot more opportunities

01:29:30.220 --> 01:29:33.000
[Guest]: in front of us than what people in the 70s or 80s had.

01:29:33.000 --> 01:29:36.760
[Guest]: I mean, if you are really, you know, bright, you have the world to conquer, right from

01:29:36.760 --> 01:29:39.480
[Guest]: here to the United States to everywhere.

01:29:39.480 --> 01:29:45.840
[Guest]: Two, I mean, because there's so much, you know, for example, you know, somebody in Delhi

01:29:45.840 --> 01:29:50.960
[Guest]: who goes to a private school today, a group private school goes to a good public or say,

01:29:50.960 --> 01:29:54.200
[Guest]: you know, went to Sardar Patel Vidyalaya, you went to Ashoka University, you came back

01:29:54.200 --> 01:29:59.280
[Guest]: with a PhD, you would have absolutely no idea of what the common people think in this country

01:29:59.280 --> 01:30:01.280
[Guest]: because you've never engaged with them.

01:30:01.280 --> 01:30:05.680
[Guest]: So the kind of class ghettoization, which is, you know, being imposed, even if inadvertently

01:30:05.680 --> 01:30:10.680
[Guest]: on you, I mean, how do you build a connect with the masses, I think these are very serious

01:30:10.680 --> 01:30:15.360
[Guest]: sociological economic questions, which people from the opposition, I think.

01:30:15.360 --> 01:30:19.960
[Guest]: So when Narendra Modi makes that critique about Rahul Gandhi of him being entitled part

01:30:19.960 --> 01:30:20.960
[Guest]: of it is true.

01:30:20.960 --> 01:30:24.380
[Guest]: I mean, it is not it is it is purely an accident of birth and Rahul Gandhi is not to blame

01:30:24.380 --> 01:30:25.460
[Guest]: for it.

01:30:25.460 --> 01:30:31.100
[Guest]: But the kind of India Rahul Gandhi or Narendra Modi would have seen are very different.

01:30:31.100 --> 01:30:33.960
[Guest]: Now Rahul Gandhi tried bringing those kind of people in the organization.

01:30:33.960 --> 01:30:39.720
[Guest]: But I think unless you have a subjective factor, unless you have a robust critique of you know,

01:30:39.720 --> 01:30:44.080
[Guest]: what the BJP stands for as a Hindu party, if you can offer a better alternative to that,

01:30:44.080 --> 01:30:47.080
[Guest]: I think it will be very difficult to build an alternative going on from here, either

01:30:47.080 --> 01:30:48.400
[Guest]: for the Congress or anybody else.

01:30:48.400 --> 01:30:52.520
[Amit Varma]: Quick note for my listeners, he mentioned Venezuela, I did have an episode on Venezuela

01:30:52.520 --> 01:30:54.880
[Amit Varma]: as well, which will be linked from the show notes.

01:30:54.880 --> 01:31:00.520
[Amit Varma]: Would it be fair to sum up your point by saying that the point that you're making is that

01:31:00.520 --> 01:31:05.560
[Amit Varma]: if you look at Narendra Modi's trajectory, he is here today because he joined a party,

01:31:05.560 --> 01:31:08.280
[Amit Varma]: a political party, which wasn't doing so well at the time.

01:31:08.280 --> 01:31:12.200
[Amit Varma]: So he didn't join it for the lust for power, but because of a deep ideological belief with

01:31:12.200 --> 01:31:17.680
[Amit Varma]: whatever the core vision of the party was, and that drove him and many others like him.

01:31:17.680 --> 01:31:21.940
[Amit Varma]: And obviously, you see the one person who got to the top to actually form the backbone

01:31:21.940 --> 01:31:23.320
[Amit Varma]: of the BJP.

01:31:23.320 --> 01:31:27.240
[Amit Varma]: And if someone joins the Congress or the left now, what is that vision which is being sold

01:31:27.240 --> 01:31:30.520
[Amit Varma]: at one point of time, that vision used to be there.

01:31:30.520 --> 01:31:35.240
[Amit Varma]: No, and you know what you said about Rahul Gandhi and the entitlement and you know, the

01:31:35.240 --> 01:31:39.120
[Amit Varma]: class barrier also reminds me of, you know, Mahua Mitra, who's very much the flavor of

01:31:39.120 --> 01:31:42.520
[Amit Varma]: the town right now gave a recent interview where she said she was once in the Congress,

01:31:42.520 --> 01:31:48.280
[Amit Varma]: as you know, in the youth wing or such like, and she was there for some time.

01:31:48.280 --> 01:31:53.560
[Amit Varma]: And then she left and she she left because a there was sexism, she wasn't being taken

01:31:53.560 --> 01:31:58.520
[Amit Varma]: seriously because she was a woman be she found that even regardless of gender, there was

01:31:58.520 --> 01:32:03.680
[Amit Varma]: a ceiling and you needed to be to have some political backing to get ahead of it.

01:32:03.680 --> 01:32:07.280
[Amit Varma]: And in a party like that, which suffers from that kind of feudal mindset, you're really

01:32:07.280 --> 01:32:12.160
[Amit Varma]: not going to rise up the ranks and someone like a Narendra Modi from an OBC background

01:32:12.160 --> 01:32:16.680
[Amit Varma]: and you know, from the kind of poor background where he came isn't going to rise up a party

01:32:16.680 --> 01:32:17.680
[Amit Varma]: like that.

01:32:17.680 --> 01:32:19.200
[Amit Varma]: And that's that's sort of something that

01:32:19.200 --> 01:32:23.680
[Guest]: Congress is not the only such party, a lot of these regional parties, including Mitra's

01:32:23.680 --> 01:32:28.040
[Guest]: own party, we know that it is not run on what exactly can be termed as democratic principles.

01:32:28.040 --> 01:32:29.040
[Guest]: Exactly.

01:32:29.040 --> 01:32:31.880
[Guest]: So I did not go into these details, because we are talking about larger issues.

01:32:31.880 --> 01:32:36.560
[Guest]: So if you want to take BJP's ideology head on, you have to have an ideological affinity

01:32:36.560 --> 01:32:42.640
[Guest]: for your own political project, which can't be ridiculing everything which is Hindutva.

01:32:42.640 --> 01:32:43.640
[Amit Varma]: It can't just be opposition.

01:32:43.640 --> 01:32:46.360
[Amit Varma]: You can't stand for something, you can't put off people.

01:32:46.360 --> 01:32:48.440
[Guest]: I mean, this is something the opposition doesn't understand.

01:32:48.440 --> 01:32:52.400
[Guest]: I mean, just because you do not like Narendra Modi, you cannot ridicule that he's going

01:32:52.400 --> 01:32:53.600
[Guest]: to be on this discovery show.

01:32:53.600 --> 01:32:56.760
[Guest]: It doesn't help your political cause, let me be as blunt as that.

01:32:56.760 --> 01:32:59.620
[Guest]: The pro-BJP people actually enjoy those things.

01:32:59.620 --> 01:33:04.480
[Guest]: You have to have a more substantive, material, effective critique.

01:33:04.480 --> 01:33:10.040
[Amit Varma]: And also just because someone is pro-BJP doesn't mean that he can't stick to those sort of

01:33:10.040 --> 01:33:13.480
[Amit Varma]: beliefs which make him pro-BJP but still find a reason to support you.

01:33:13.480 --> 01:33:16.560
[Amit Varma]: For example, so I'm just throwing a thought at you, tell me what you think.

01:33:16.560 --> 01:33:19.600
[Amit Varma]: I think that you can't categorize people very simply.

01:33:19.600 --> 01:33:23.800
[Amit Varma]: We all contain multitudes and there might be an individual who is a believing Hindu

01:33:23.800 --> 01:33:26.160
[Amit Varma]: and who believes in the BJP project.

01:33:26.160 --> 01:33:30.200
[Amit Varma]: But he might also have liberal instincts and he believes in free speech and he might also

01:33:30.200 --> 01:33:31.760
[Amit Varma]: believe in free markets or whatever.

01:33:31.760 --> 01:33:37.720
[Amit Varma]: We are a bundle of impulses and what the BJP political project has very successfully done

01:33:37.720 --> 01:33:41.920
[Amit Varma]: is appeal to one aspect of their belief systems.

01:33:41.920 --> 01:33:44.380
[Amit Varma]: And for that reason, they support BJP.

01:33:44.380 --> 01:33:49.800
[Amit Varma]: But you know, it is still nevertheless, I would believe possible for other parties to

01:33:49.800 --> 01:33:56.680
[Amit Varma]: appeal to other aspects of their beliefs and whatever, you know, very complex multifaceted

01:33:56.680 --> 01:34:00.440
[Amit Varma]: worldviews are and draw some of that support away.

01:34:00.440 --> 01:34:05.280
[Amit Varma]: Now given that a lot of the work that you do, which deals with data is like any political

01:34:05.280 --> 01:34:08.880
[Amit Varma]: data is also in its nature, I would guess social data.

01:34:08.880 --> 01:34:11.000
[Guest]: What would your thoughts be on this observation?

01:34:11.000 --> 01:34:13.120
[Guest]: You're exactly right.

01:34:13.120 --> 01:34:18.960
[Guest]: This was in 2016, I guess, CSDS Lokniti, which is among the few credible political research

01:34:18.960 --> 01:34:22.400
[Guest]: institutes in our country, they did a survey of youth.

01:34:22.400 --> 01:34:24.440
[Guest]: So they had this questionnaire, they went along to everybody.

01:34:24.440 --> 01:34:27.280
[Guest]: One of the questions in the questionnaire was which political party do you support?

01:34:27.280 --> 01:34:31.920
[Guest]: There were a host of other questions, you know, ranging from do you support eating beef

01:34:31.920 --> 01:34:38.560
[Guest]: to you know, whether somebody who consumes alcohol should be your neighbor, etc, etc.

01:34:38.560 --> 01:34:43.480
[Guest]: When we ran cross task, what it shows was that apart from the question of eating beef,

01:34:43.480 --> 01:34:47.080
[Guest]: there was by and large complete political concurrence among supporters of different political

01:34:47.080 --> 01:34:50.400
[Guest]: parties, whether you supported the BJP or the Congress or anybody else, there was absolutely

01:34:50.400 --> 01:34:51.400
[Guest]: no difference.

01:34:51.400 --> 01:34:57.840
[Guest]: So your sociological beliefs, you know, your behavioral beliefs, I think are more or less

01:34:57.840 --> 01:35:01.600
[Guest]: shaped by your socialization rather than anything else, rather than which political party do

01:35:01.600 --> 01:35:02.600
[Guest]: you support.

01:35:02.600 --> 01:35:06.400
[Guest]: If you were to go to say, South Bombay, and if you were to go to Gaya, the place I come

01:35:06.400 --> 01:35:11.360
[Guest]: from, I mean, what is acceptable socially and what is not acceptable socially would

01:35:11.360 --> 01:35:13.000
[Guest]: probably be very different.

01:35:13.000 --> 01:35:16.920
[Guest]: And you cannot brand the person living in say, South Bombay or Gaya and be that as may

01:35:16.920 --> 01:35:22.760
[Guest]: in either cases, as being prejudiced or biased, or I think social change has to be something

01:35:22.760 --> 01:35:28.080
[Guest]: which you consistently strive for, which is where no, I think, you know, take lynchings,

01:35:28.080 --> 01:35:34.280
[Guest]: for example, what is the by and by now the established liberal reaction to lynchings?

01:35:34.280 --> 01:35:37.960
[Guest]: Something happens, I think both you and I agree that it is completely unfortunate.

01:35:37.960 --> 01:35:40.800
[Guest]: Then you have a protest here in Delhi, etc.

01:35:40.800 --> 01:35:45.560
[Guest]: Where is the preemptive political effort to prevent such things from happening?

01:35:45.560 --> 01:35:47.160
[Guest]: Has the opposition done a campaign?

01:35:47.160 --> 01:35:50.640
[Guest]: Now, some people like Harsh Mandar, etc, have tried to do it, but they are individuals.

01:35:50.640 --> 01:35:53.480
[Guest]: I mean, I mean, you can't have that kind of an impact.

01:35:53.480 --> 01:35:57.480
[Guest]: If you want to prevent a religious polarization in this country, where is the preemptive political

01:35:57.480 --> 01:35:59.320
[Guest]: effort to do that?

01:35:59.320 --> 01:36:03.480
[Guest]: I mean, it is extremely convenient for a bunch of political actors to come out everything

01:36:03.480 --> 01:36:06.480
[Guest]: ex post after say this thing has happened, where's the ex ante effort?

01:36:06.480 --> 01:36:07.480
[Guest]: I don't see that.

01:36:07.480 --> 01:36:11.560
[Guest]: Then how can you go and say that, you know, people people are becoming bigger, they don't

01:36:11.560 --> 01:36:12.560
[Guest]: listen to us.

01:36:12.560 --> 01:36:15.840
[Guest]: I think that's that's intellectual and political lethargy.

01:36:15.840 --> 01:36:19.440
[Amit Varma]: So we've spoken about the BJP, we've spoken about the Congress.

01:36:19.440 --> 01:36:22.600
[Amit Varma]: Let's speak about the left because you've been a man of the left yourself.

01:36:22.600 --> 01:36:26.200
[Amit Varma]: And I'm sure what has happened over the last few years must pain you, though it doesn't

01:36:26.200 --> 01:36:28.480
[Amit Varma]: pain me, but I'm sure it must pain you.

01:36:28.480 --> 01:36:29.920
[Amit Varma]: Is the left dead?

01:36:29.920 --> 01:36:31.040
[Amit Varma]: What did they do wrong?

01:36:31.040 --> 01:36:32.680
[Guest]: What happened?

01:36:32.680 --> 01:36:38.760
[Guest]: The political left as we knew it, I see it very difficult that it will revive.

01:36:38.760 --> 01:36:41.560
[Guest]: I don't think that's going to happen.

01:36:41.560 --> 01:36:44.080
[Guest]: Now, has it all happened in the same way?

01:36:44.080 --> 01:36:48.120
[Guest]: No, let us take the Bengal and Kerala examples, the two states where left was actually very

01:36:48.120 --> 01:36:49.520
[Guest]: strong.

01:36:49.520 --> 01:36:53.480
[Guest]: The Bengal thing, I think is a classic case of complete ideological disarray, because

01:36:53.480 --> 01:36:57.760
[Guest]: you ultimately ended up I mean, I think there's been a lot of serious academic work, there

01:36:57.760 --> 01:37:01.200
[Guest]: were a lot of problems with, you know, the left front government when it was in power.

01:37:01.200 --> 01:37:05.640
[Guest]: If you look at the social indicators, etc, Dwaipayan Bhattacharya, who is a professor

01:37:05.640 --> 01:37:09.440
[Guest]: of political science in JNU has written a very good book, you know, it's, it's called

01:37:09.440 --> 01:37:15.280
[Guest]: governance as practice, how left got consumed in its own contradictions, gives a very powerful

01:37:15.280 --> 01:37:16.280
[Guest]: account of what happened.

01:37:16.280 --> 01:37:20.160
[Guest]: But ultimately, you basically lost power on the question of acquiring land for a handful

01:37:20.160 --> 01:37:21.160
[Guest]: of corporates.

01:37:21.160 --> 01:37:25.240
[Guest]: Now, that's the worst way in which a communist party would like to lose power.

01:37:25.240 --> 01:37:27.180
[Guest]: Let's go to Kerala now.

01:37:27.180 --> 01:37:32.520
[Guest]: I think Pinarayi Vijayan's government and the CPIM and the LDF there took a very principled

01:37:32.520 --> 01:37:34.480
[Guest]: position when it came to the question of Sabarimala.

01:37:34.480 --> 01:37:37.920
[Guest]: They were the only political actors in the state, the Congress and the BJP both sort

01:37:37.920 --> 01:37:42.640
[Guest]: of decided against doing it, who stood for the Supreme Court judgment that women of menstruating

01:37:42.640 --> 01:37:45.200
[Guest]: age should be allowed to enter the holy shrine.

01:37:45.200 --> 01:37:48.400
[Guest]: I think this electoral loss is a political price for doing that.

01:37:48.400 --> 01:37:52.280
[Guest]: Now they have lost from a politically very principled, this is something I think even

01:37:52.280 --> 01:37:53.280
[Guest]: you would agree with.

01:37:53.280 --> 01:37:54.280
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, yeah, absolutely.

01:37:54.280 --> 01:37:57.880
[Guest]: But in Tripura, it took a completely different turn.

01:37:57.880 --> 01:38:01.800
[Guest]: I think somewhere between the Bengali and the tribal contradiction, they lost the plot

01:38:01.800 --> 01:38:04.360
[Guest]: and ended up losing a large amount of tribal vote.

01:38:04.360 --> 01:38:07.280
[Guest]: And once they lost power, it has all led to a meltdown.

01:38:07.280 --> 01:38:11.480
[Guest]: So if one were to talk about the electoral decline of the left, I think one has to take

01:38:11.480 --> 01:38:17.360
[Guest]: a heterogeneous view, because each stronghold, how the left lost it, I'm not so sure whether

01:38:17.360 --> 01:38:18.800
[Guest]: they come back in Kerala or not.

01:38:18.800 --> 01:38:23.120
[Guest]: But let us for a moment assume that there are all different factors.

01:38:23.120 --> 01:38:27.600
[Guest]: But the larger factor and a lot of, you know, political leaders in the left like to say,

01:38:27.600 --> 01:38:31.040
[Guest]: but that why should these states be held accountable for the decline of the left?

01:38:31.040 --> 01:38:32.440
[Guest]: What about the rest of the country?

01:38:32.440 --> 01:38:36.680
[Guest]: Why did the rest of the party say not support the Bengal party or the Kerala party?

01:38:36.680 --> 01:38:40.720
[Guest]: That is where the ideological question I think becomes extremely important.

01:38:40.720 --> 01:38:43.440
[Guest]: That what is it you want to mobilize people on?

01:38:43.440 --> 01:38:48.080
[Guest]: Now let us look at some progressive legislations which happened during the UPF 1.

01:38:48.080 --> 01:38:53.560
[Guest]: The left played a role in all of them, Rural Employment Guarantee, Right to Information,

01:38:53.560 --> 01:38:54.560
[Guest]: Forest Rights Act.

01:38:54.560 --> 01:38:57.920
[Guest]: I think the left had not been supporting the UPF government, these legislations probably

01:38:57.920 --> 01:39:00.720
[Guest]: would never have seen the light of the day.

01:39:00.720 --> 01:39:07.480
[Guest]: Interestingly, the left did not start the agitations for demanding these agitations.

01:39:07.480 --> 01:39:10.440
[Guest]: Employment Guarantee started from the Right to Food Campaign.

01:39:10.440 --> 01:39:14.960
[Guest]: Right to Information was Aruna Roy, Arvind Kejriwal, a lot of these other people.

01:39:14.960 --> 01:39:18.680
[Guest]: Forest Rights Act bill was a lot of tribal organizations, I mean, there were some left

01:39:18.680 --> 01:39:20.880
[Guest]: leaning organizations also.

01:39:20.880 --> 01:39:25.120
[Guest]: So even these little successes against the Indian state, which you think actually democratize

01:39:25.120 --> 01:39:30.120
[Guest]: the state further, tilt the balance if one could say so in favor of the extremely marginalized.

01:39:30.120 --> 01:39:33.560
[Guest]: Now, these are extremely marginalized sections of the society.

01:39:33.560 --> 01:39:35.720
[Guest]: The left did not take an initiative on its own.

01:39:35.720 --> 01:39:41.640
[Guest]: Where is the left really strong today, despite all its political setbacks?

01:39:41.640 --> 01:39:45.640
[Guest]: Bank unions, insurance unions, these are the ones, you know, if the public sector bank

01:39:45.640 --> 01:39:48.960
[Guest]: unions decide, which are still dominated by the left, they'll bring the banking industry

01:39:48.960 --> 01:39:53.640
[Guest]: to a complete standstill in our country, handful of universities, students unions, etc.

01:39:53.640 --> 01:40:00.320
[Guest]: So you actually have a situation where your remaining political capital rests with people

01:40:00.320 --> 01:40:03.640
[Guest]: who are fast becoming marginalized in their own way.

01:40:03.640 --> 01:40:06.680
[Guest]: We know that public sector banking is not going to be the future of banking in this

01:40:06.680 --> 01:40:07.680
[Guest]: country.

01:40:07.680 --> 01:40:10.200
[Guest]: Whether the government privatizes banks or not is a different debate.

01:40:10.200 --> 01:40:14.760
[Guest]: But 20 years from now, public sector banks would not be what they are today.

01:40:14.760 --> 01:40:19.280
[Guest]: So between these two extremes, you know, this is something the left exploited early in its

01:40:19.280 --> 01:40:20.280
[Guest]: career, etc.

01:40:20.280 --> 01:40:25.800
[Guest]: I mean, it had a lot of ideology, you know, Jyoti Basu was a lawyer educated in England,

01:40:25.800 --> 01:40:27.480
[Guest]: he came back and did that politics.

01:40:27.480 --> 01:40:32.360
[Guest]: So I mean, we spoke about Narendra Modi, who comes from a very modest family, had very

01:40:32.360 --> 01:40:36.600
[Guest]: little education, and was not successfully professionally otherwise, but became a political

01:40:36.600 --> 01:40:37.600
[Guest]: old timer.

01:40:37.600 --> 01:40:41.560
[Guest]: Now, here is the other extreme Jyoti Basu, who comes from England is educated in England

01:40:41.560 --> 01:40:45.960
[Guest]: could have no and all the money in his life, decides to work for a communist party.

01:40:45.960 --> 01:40:50.720
[Guest]: So there was also the other side of the political infatuation, affinity, whatever one might

01:40:50.720 --> 01:40:55.440
[Guest]: choose to call it, it actually, the Bombay film industry at one point of time, today

01:40:55.440 --> 01:41:00.120
[Guest]: people rave and rant about Akshay Kumar supporting Narendra Modi, etc.

01:41:00.120 --> 01:41:04.760
[Guest]: I mean, the Communist Party actually had its headquarters in Bombay, the entire Indian

01:41:04.760 --> 01:41:08.880
[Guest]: People's Theatre Association, the galaxy of film stars used to work for the left.

01:41:08.880 --> 01:41:14.320
[Guest]: So how do you regain that ideological, I think, and I can say this with a lot of confidence

01:41:14.320 --> 01:41:19.400
[Guest]: for the left without a larger ideological narrative, left politics cannot have any future

01:41:19.400 --> 01:41:20.400
[Guest]: in any society.

01:41:20.400 --> 01:41:25.360
[Guest]: I mean, your your basic justification for your politics, even today comes from the fact

01:41:25.360 --> 01:41:30.280
[Guest]: that there is a established school of analysis in social sciences, which was founded by Marx,

01:41:30.280 --> 01:41:34.920
[Guest]: which has been improved upon by a lot of thinkers, because left politics, by definition is a

01:41:34.920 --> 01:41:36.320
[Guest]: scientific way of politics.

01:41:36.320 --> 01:41:39.760
[Guest]: And that is what the left likes to claim it is people might have disagreements with it.

01:41:39.760 --> 01:41:42.800
[Guest]: So even if you disagree with the left, you say that the basic problem is in the theory,

01:41:42.800 --> 01:41:45.580
[Guest]: I mean, it is not that people do it wrong.

01:41:45.580 --> 01:41:48.960
[Guest]: So the left has to think about going back to the drawing board on that.

01:41:48.960 --> 01:41:50.920
[Guest]: Now, where do you get your people?

01:41:50.920 --> 01:41:54.840
[Guest]: You don't have factories, you can't have trade unions, farmer politics, etc.

01:41:54.840 --> 01:41:58.600
[Guest]: You today, even if you were to say that I want to do land reforms, no farmer would come

01:41:58.600 --> 01:42:03.320
[Guest]: to you a land has become hopelessly fragmented, be nobody wants to be in farming.

01:42:03.320 --> 01:42:04.960
[Guest]: So where do you draw your ranks from?

01:42:04.960 --> 01:42:06.480
[Guest]: I think is a very important question.

01:42:06.480 --> 01:42:10.000
[Guest]: This is a question which is not very easy to answer.

01:42:10.000 --> 01:42:14.200
[Guest]: But the existing leadership of the left, I don't think has even made an attempt to answer

01:42:14.200 --> 01:42:15.200
[Amit Varma]: that question.

01:42:15.200 --> 01:42:18.120
[Amit Varma]: And what strikes me and obviously, I don't know the left as deeply as you do.

01:42:18.120 --> 01:42:20.920
[Amit Varma]: So feel free to sort of tell me if you disagree.

01:42:20.920 --> 01:42:24.880
[Amit Varma]: But what also strikes me is that these sort of theoretical debates that you speak of are

01:42:24.880 --> 01:42:28.960
[Amit Varma]: something that might be happening in academic circles, but how does a common man think of

01:42:28.960 --> 01:42:29.960
[Amit Varma]: the left?

01:42:29.960 --> 01:42:33.120
[Amit Varma]: And why has the left gained traction wherever it has with the common man?

01:42:33.120 --> 01:42:37.080
[Amit Varma]: And the reason partly is, of course, a reaction against an oppressive state.

01:42:37.080 --> 01:42:41.880
[Amit Varma]: And apart from that, a certain sort of pro poor rhetoric that you know, the rich are

01:42:41.880 --> 01:42:46.000
[Amit Varma]: exploiting you and will, you know, redistribute their wealth a little bit and will make society

01:42:46.000 --> 01:42:47.120
[Amit Varma]: more equal.

01:42:47.120 --> 01:42:51.800
[Amit Varma]: But what seems to have happened in recent times is that that narrative has been co opted

01:42:51.800 --> 01:42:55.080
[Amit Varma]: by the BJP, like you mentioned the NREGA.

01:42:55.080 --> 01:42:59.040
[Amit Varma]: And you know, one of the multiple factors, which I have read about from reporters, you

01:42:59.040 --> 01:43:04.640
[Amit Varma]: know, I think Parth MN reported on this extensively before the elections, is that a lot of people

01:43:04.640 --> 01:43:09.160
[Amit Varma]: seem to have voted for the BJP because of the social welfare schemes, because of the

01:43:09.160 --> 01:43:13.800
[Amit Varma]: delivery, the last minute delivery of the social welfare schemes, sometimes when they

01:43:13.800 --> 01:43:16.960
[Amit Varma]: benefited themselves, and sometimes when they saw others benefiting and said, hey, maybe

01:43:16.960 --> 01:43:19.000
[Amit Varma]: I can also benefit in future.

01:43:19.000 --> 01:43:24.120
[Amit Varma]: So that whole pro poor populist narrative has, seems to me to have been co opted by

01:43:24.120 --> 01:43:29.760
[Amit Varma]: the BJP, which then then you wondered at what space in the popular imagination, forget the

01:43:29.760 --> 01:43:33.760
[Amit Varma]: theory, what space in the popular imagination can the left possibly occupy now?

01:43:33.760 --> 01:43:35.960
[Guest]: Well, that's one way to look at it.

01:43:35.960 --> 01:43:40.040
[Guest]: But let me pose a counter question, let us say the people voted for the BJP because they

01:43:40.040 --> 01:43:44.960
[Guest]: got toilets and houses, Swachh Bharat and this Pradhan Mantri Awas Yojana, perfectly

01:43:44.960 --> 01:43:48.480
[Guest]: all right for people to vote for the BJP in one election.

01:43:48.480 --> 01:43:52.680
[Guest]: Is that going to be enough for them to vote for the BJP again, because politics the beauty

01:43:52.680 --> 01:43:57.720
[Guest]: of it is it's it's, it's an infinite process, it's not a one off thing.

01:43:57.720 --> 01:44:00.320
[Guest]: Now will Narendra Modi give them another toilet and another house?

01:44:00.320 --> 01:44:01.320
[Guest]: Probably not.

01:44:01.320 --> 01:44:04.480
[Guest]: Because there's a limit to the amount of welfarism even this government can do, I mean, you don't

01:44:04.480 --> 01:44:06.200
[Guest]: have those kinds of resources.

01:44:06.200 --> 01:44:14.680
[Guest]: So, you know, the question is, you know, can you mobilize people who were given say a one

01:44:14.680 --> 01:44:20.360
[Guest]: time asset transfer by a government to demand something more?

01:44:20.360 --> 01:44:26.480
[Guest]: If a political party were to start a movement in this country today, that we don't just

01:44:26.480 --> 01:44:29.200
[Guest]: need schools in our country, we need better schools.

01:44:29.200 --> 01:44:34.040
[Guest]: There's a lot of talk about this learning outcomes, we need learning outcomes to improve,

01:44:34.040 --> 01:44:38.680
[Guest]: no, because children when even when they get out of school after class 10th or 12th, they

01:44:38.680 --> 01:44:42.560
[Guest]: can't speak, they can't write, this is something we directly affects your employability.

01:44:42.560 --> 01:44:46.520
[Guest]: I mean, even if you want to, you know, work as an assistant at a grocery shop, the shopkeeper

01:44:46.520 --> 01:44:49.880
[Guest]: would expect that you probably do the basic maths and a lot of people find that very difficult

01:44:49.880 --> 01:44:50.880
[Amit Varma]: in our country.

01:44:50.880 --> 01:44:55.960
[Amit Varma]: In fact, a small part of the jobs crisis is also the disconnect between the jobs and education.

01:44:55.960 --> 01:44:57.640
[Guest]: It's a large part of the job crisis.

01:44:57.640 --> 01:45:01.720
[Guest]: I mean, you might have an MPhil degree, but so what I mean, how do you make yourself employable?

01:45:01.720 --> 01:45:02.720
[Guest]: What are you good for?

01:45:02.720 --> 01:45:03.720
[Guest]: Yeah.

01:45:03.720 --> 01:45:07.920
[Guest]: Especially in provincial universities, things are really bad.

01:45:07.920 --> 01:45:10.800
[Guest]: syllabi have not been revised for 30-40 years.

01:45:10.800 --> 01:45:14.680
[Guest]: Most of them work with my father teaches in a college in Gaya, so I know, I mean, he has

01:45:14.680 --> 01:45:17.360
[Guest]: to take care of 1000 students with the strength of three teachers.

01:45:17.360 --> 01:45:21.920
[Guest]: So I mean, you can't teach it's humanly not possible, you go nuts if you try to do that.

01:45:21.920 --> 01:45:27.480
[Guest]: So if a political party were to take that thing, mobilize the youth, I think it could

01:45:27.480 --> 01:45:29.040
[Guest]: lead to results.

01:45:29.040 --> 01:45:32.640
[Guest]: And if the government know to prevent the opposition from winning does it, then that's

01:45:32.640 --> 01:45:33.640
[Guest]: the best case scenario.

01:45:33.640 --> 01:45:37.640
[Guest]: I mean, then you've completely sort of radically transformed your education system, which would

01:45:37.640 --> 01:45:40.320
[Guest]: make you use your demographic dividend in a better way.

01:45:40.320 --> 01:45:45.120
[Guest]: I think one of the biggest reasons for the problem, whether it is a left etc, is that

01:45:45.120 --> 01:45:49.800
[Guest]: the people who are at the top, who are making decisions of what needs to be done, what doesn't

01:45:49.800 --> 01:45:56.760
[Guest]: need to be done, have absolutely no connect with the, yeah, let me be harsh.

01:45:56.760 --> 01:46:01.880
[Guest]: I think the left leadership in this country is a bunch of bureaucrats awaiting retirement.

01:46:01.880 --> 01:46:06.480
[Amit Varma]: It's very interesting that the political marketplace has transformed itself.

01:46:06.480 --> 01:46:10.840
[Amit Varma]: Many existing players haven't been able to adapt, like the Congress and the left.

01:46:10.840 --> 01:46:14.680
[Amit Varma]: However, there is a space for new entrepreneurs and this is demonstrated by the example you

01:46:14.680 --> 01:46:20.120
[Amit Varma]: gave earlier of the Aam Aadmi Party in Delhi, where they came up and they found an issue

01:46:20.120 --> 01:46:24.040
[Amit Varma]: like corruption, and they took it and they made a space for themselves within the political

01:46:24.040 --> 01:46:25.040
[Amit Varma]: marketplace.

01:46:25.040 --> 01:46:26.920
[Amit Varma]: Whether you agree with them or not is a different matter.

01:46:26.920 --> 01:46:29.800
[Amit Varma]: It's a it's a triumph of political entrepreneurship.

01:46:29.800 --> 01:46:32.960
[Amit Varma]: And like you pointed out, maybe education is another wedge factor or whatever.

01:46:32.960 --> 01:46:37.960
[Amit Varma]: This is up to political entrepreneurs to figure out what sort of narratives they can find

01:46:37.960 --> 01:46:43.120
[Amit Varma]: and which which brings me to my next question, which is the politics of identity, or the

01:46:43.120 --> 01:46:47.960
[Amit Varma]: politics of Mandal as it were, which, you know, received a big Philip around 18991,

01:46:47.960 --> 01:46:51.320
[Amit Varma]: you know, those years.

01:46:51.320 --> 01:46:56.960
[Amit Varma]: And there was sort of the consensus view of Indian politics was that it is essentially

01:46:56.960 --> 01:46:59.000
[Amit Varma]: a politics of identity.

01:46:59.000 --> 01:47:03.760
[Amit Varma]: Even when the 2014 win of the BJP was being analyzed, it was okay, these are the different

01:47:03.760 --> 01:47:06.480
[Amit Varma]: kinds of caste coalitions you made, and so on.

01:47:06.480 --> 01:47:10.040
[Amit Varma]: And now there is a counter view coming up saying that that has changed completely.

01:47:10.040 --> 01:47:15.160
[Amit Varma]: And a lot of these smaller identities have been subsumed within this larger Hindu identity.

01:47:15.160 --> 01:47:18.360
[Amit Varma]: And that is a triumph of Modi and Shah.

01:47:18.360 --> 01:47:20.480
[Amit Varma]: What's your sense of this?

01:47:20.480 --> 01:47:23.880
[Guest]: I am not so sure.

01:47:23.880 --> 01:47:28.360
[Guest]: There is definitely an element of Hindutva in the BJP's political success today is true.

01:47:28.360 --> 01:47:30.760
[Guest]: They should dispute that.

01:47:30.760 --> 01:47:33.120
[Guest]: Does it mean that the caste identities do not matter?

01:47:33.120 --> 01:47:34.120
[Guest]: I do not think so.

01:47:34.120 --> 01:47:38.880
[Guest]: I mean, a lot of thought goes in ticket distribution, we know for a fact, you know, even for the

01:47:38.880 --> 01:47:41.280
[Guest]: BJP, caste equations are paramount for them.

01:47:41.280 --> 01:47:43.400
[Guest]: Look at Karnataka, for example.

01:47:43.400 --> 01:47:48.240
[Guest]: I mean, Yadurappa has become the chief minister, he's a Lingayat leader, he's not a Hindu leader

01:47:48.240 --> 01:47:49.240
[Guest]: in Karnataka.

01:47:49.240 --> 01:47:54.200
[Guest]: I mean, that is the core identity with the BJP thrives on politically in the state.

01:47:54.200 --> 01:48:00.360
[Guest]: But the Hindu consolidation, we also have to understand how it has been achieved.

01:48:00.360 --> 01:48:05.400
[Guest]: I think, you know, the othering of Muslims is just one part of it.

01:48:05.400 --> 01:48:11.080
[Guest]: But in places like Bihar, Uttar Pradesh, it has also been achieved against the erstwhile

01:48:11.080 --> 01:48:14.380
[Guest]: dominant Yadavs, Jatavs, etc.

01:48:14.380 --> 01:48:17.100
[Guest]: So that is also a very integral part of the Hindu consolidation.

01:48:17.100 --> 01:48:21.640
[Guest]: So the BJP is still at around 35% of the vote, it is not the case that they've reached 60-65%

01:48:21.640 --> 01:48:22.640
[Guest]: of the vote.

01:48:22.640 --> 01:48:27.400
[Guest]: I think, and this varies a lot across states, there is a lot of social tension in the BJP's

01:48:27.400 --> 01:48:29.600
[Guest]: ranks regarding the caste thing also.

01:48:29.600 --> 01:48:32.400
[Guest]: All of us saw how the BJP struggled to balance caste equations.

01:48:32.400 --> 01:48:36.120
[Guest]: So when the Madhya Pradesh, Rajasthan, Chhattisgarh defeats came, it was said that there was a

01:48:36.120 --> 01:48:41.440
[Guest]: lot of pent up anger among the upper caste about how the BJP, you know, nullified the

01:48:41.440 --> 01:48:45.560
[Guest]: Supreme Court's amendments to the SCST Prevention of Atrocities Act, that there was a feeling

01:48:45.560 --> 01:48:50.200
[Guest]: that the BJP was being pro-Dalit, which who were victimizing upper caste, was the claim.

01:48:50.200 --> 01:48:52.880
[Guest]: I'm not saying true or false.

01:48:52.880 --> 01:48:53.880
[Guest]: What did the BJP do?

01:48:53.880 --> 01:48:57.680
[Guest]: The BJP brought reservation for economically weaker sections from upper caste who had never

01:48:57.680 --> 01:48:59.280
[Guest]: had reservations.

01:48:59.280 --> 01:49:03.240
[Guest]: This is a complete game changer as far as social justice politics is considered in this

01:49:03.240 --> 01:49:04.240
[Guest]: country.

01:49:04.240 --> 01:49:05.840
[Guest]: The BJP does not stop here.

01:49:05.840 --> 01:49:06.840
[Guest]: Then what did it do?

01:49:06.840 --> 01:49:08.720
[Guest]: Then another case came in the Supreme Court.

01:49:08.720 --> 01:49:12.280
[Guest]: This was about implementing reservations in higher educational institutions.

01:49:12.280 --> 01:49:15.640
[Guest]: So the question was whether you implement reservations at the level of a department

01:49:15.640 --> 01:49:18.720
[Guest]: or do you implement reservations at the level of the institution?

01:49:18.720 --> 01:49:22.000
[Guest]: If you did so at the level of the department, the number of effective seats would be very

01:49:22.000 --> 01:49:23.000
[Guest]: high.

01:49:23.000 --> 01:49:27.120
[Guest]: There, the BJP government actually once again nullified the Supreme Court order, but in

01:49:27.120 --> 01:49:31.520
[Guest]: favor of the socially deprived caste, it was a completely anti-upper caste thing.

01:49:31.520 --> 01:49:36.320
[Guest]: So it is doing a lot of flip flop between both camps and trying to keep both the camps

01:49:36.320 --> 01:49:37.320
[Guest]: happy.

01:49:37.320 --> 01:49:43.160
[Guest]: OBCs, now we have the talks of an OBC reorganization commission, there is talk that three categories

01:49:43.160 --> 01:49:47.380
[Guest]: within the 27% OBC reservation would be made where the communities which have benefited

01:49:47.380 --> 01:49:52.200
[Guest]: the most from OBC reservation would only have 7% instead of 27%.

01:49:52.200 --> 01:49:56.840
[Guest]: The BJP, I think, is doing a lot of experimentation with the identity politics in our country.

01:49:56.840 --> 01:49:58.080
[Guest]: The Congress also tried that.

01:49:58.080 --> 01:50:01.480
[Guest]: They tried to make Lingayats a religion in the Karnataka election, it completely backfired

01:50:01.480 --> 01:50:02.480
[Guest]: on them.

01:50:02.480 --> 01:50:06.640
[Guest]: The BJP before the elections in Maharashtra now has given Maratha reservation.

01:50:06.640 --> 01:50:11.360
[Guest]: Effective reservation probably has gone to some 70%, which is absurd in my personal view,

01:50:11.360 --> 01:50:13.760
[Guest]: but nevertheless, I mean, BJP doesn't mean meh.

01:50:13.760 --> 01:50:17.520
[Guest]: So I think identity continues to be a very significant part of it.

01:50:17.520 --> 01:50:23.760
[Guest]: But I also think that for an anti-BJP force to just bank on identity and counter the BJP

01:50:23.760 --> 01:50:27.360
[Guest]: has become extremely difficult, because there's a historical legacy to it.

01:50:27.360 --> 01:50:32.460
[Guest]: So if you get just the Yadavs and the Muslims, everybody else will unite against you in Bihar.

01:50:32.460 --> 01:50:36.800
[Guest]: So you basically get 30% of the vote, you don't get any seats, the opposition gets 56%,

01:50:36.800 --> 01:50:39.600
[Guest]: the NDA gets 56%, walks away with everything.

01:50:39.600 --> 01:50:43.480
[Guest]: So it only works for the BJP in today's age, identity doesn't work for the other camp.

01:50:43.480 --> 01:50:48.640
[Amit Varma]: But there must be like, if it is true that the politics of identity still matters, and

01:50:48.640 --> 01:50:52.840
[Amit Varma]: it is also true that at some point, there will be limits to how much you can gain with

01:50:52.840 --> 01:50:57.320
[Amit Varma]: patronage and some of these coalitions are bound to be uneasy coalitions and fissures

01:50:57.320 --> 01:51:00.440
[Amit Varma]: will develop and then there is possibly hope for the others there.

01:51:00.440 --> 01:51:04.280
[Guest]: Well, let's see, for example, Goa is a very interesting case, you talked about it earlier.

01:51:04.280 --> 01:51:10.600
[Guest]: So this, these MLAs from Congress resigned and went, the BJP actually dumped an existing

01:51:10.600 --> 01:51:14.720
[Guest]: ally of it sort of their ministers were removed from the cabinet, and they are feeling completely

01:51:14.720 --> 01:51:15.720
[Guest]: betrayed.

01:51:15.720 --> 01:51:18.680
[Guest]: So I'm sure there's some identity at play, I think a part of these MLAs were defected

01:51:18.680 --> 01:51:19.920
[Guest]: are Christians or something.

01:51:19.920 --> 01:51:22.080
[Guest]: So we'll have to see how it goes about.

01:51:22.080 --> 01:51:26.960
[Guest]: But like I said, what is important is these things could work at the state level, they

01:51:26.960 --> 01:51:30.360
[Guest]: could work in a Madhya Pradesh or a Rajasthan or a Chhattisgarh.

01:51:30.360 --> 01:51:35.440
[Guest]: But I think when it comes to national elections, the political appeal with Narendra Modi has

01:51:35.440 --> 01:51:39.880
[Guest]: today, and that I don't think is based on identity that is based on a very larger macro

01:51:39.880 --> 01:51:44.880
[Guest]: macho outlook of a national leader, who is not afraid to sort of strike at the enemy,

01:51:44.880 --> 01:51:49.200
[Guest]: who has taken India's prestige to completely new levels, etc.

01:51:49.200 --> 01:51:54.760
[Guest]: You cannot use identity to puncture those achievements.

01:51:54.760 --> 01:51:57.840
[Amit Varma]: So I've taken a lot of your time, we are almost reaching two hours.

01:51:57.840 --> 01:52:04.760
[Amit Varma]: So I want to end with sort of asking a question that asks you for a subjective assessment

01:52:04.760 --> 01:52:08.920
[Amit Varma]: based on objective data, which is, you know, you study data all the time.

01:52:08.920 --> 01:52:12.720
[Amit Varma]: For many years, you've been doing that you can see different trends within this country's

01:52:12.720 --> 01:52:15.860
[Amit Varma]: social trends, political trends, so on and so forth.

01:52:15.860 --> 01:52:20.320
[Amit Varma]: If I ask you to indulge me for a moment and go 10 years ahead, 10 years forward in time

01:52:20.320 --> 01:52:26.520
[Amit Varma]: to 2029, what do you think is a best case scenario and a worst case scenario for the

01:52:26.520 --> 01:52:28.920
[Amit Varma]: Indian political landscape and therefore for India?

01:52:28.920 --> 01:52:36.680
[Guest]: I mean, it's, it's, let's come to the worst case scenario, that's easy, easier to envisage.

01:52:36.680 --> 01:52:42.000
[Guest]: I think climate change would play havoc with agricultural production in the country.

01:52:42.000 --> 01:52:46.320
[Guest]: And a lot of farmers who are already you know, struggling very hard to make ends meet would

01:52:46.320 --> 01:52:50.640
[Guest]: have a very difficult time, you know, agriculture would become very difficult and financially

01:52:50.640 --> 01:52:55.000
[Guest]: unrewarding in large parts of the country.

01:52:55.000 --> 01:52:58.240
[Guest]: Food security is something we've learned to take for granted in a country for a very long

01:52:58.240 --> 01:53:00.560
[Guest]: time now.

01:53:00.560 --> 01:53:05.200
[Guest]: I'm afraid that will not be the case 20 years from now.

01:53:05.200 --> 01:53:08.320
[Guest]: This I think more than anything else is what really scares me.

01:53:08.320 --> 01:53:11.600
[Guest]: You've also written about the water crisis recently.

01:53:11.600 --> 01:53:16.760
[Guest]: The way you know, from Punjab, Haryana, which is the which are the traditional green revolution

01:53:16.760 --> 01:53:21.400
[Guest]: states to states such as Bihar, arsenic poisoning is a huge problem in Bihar now.

01:53:21.400 --> 01:53:26.220
[Guest]: I mean, Nitish Kumar has, you know, he's started a scheme which promises tap water to every

01:53:26.220 --> 01:53:30.120
[Guest]: household in a village, but basically that tap water comes from a submersible pump in

01:53:30.120 --> 01:53:31.120
[Guest]: said in the village.

01:53:31.120 --> 01:53:34.000
[Guest]: So it's not some natural water supply.

01:53:34.000 --> 01:53:36.160
[Guest]: That I think is the worst case scenario.

01:53:36.160 --> 01:53:43.640
[Guest]: The best case scenario I think would be the kind of political competition the BJP has

01:53:43.640 --> 01:53:46.200
[Guest]: brought into politics in this country.

01:53:46.200 --> 01:53:50.440
[Guest]: I think the old ossified establishments of politics, a lot of which, like you said, were

01:53:50.440 --> 01:53:53.000
[Guest]: based on patronage, identity, etc.

01:53:53.000 --> 01:53:55.060
[Guest]: I think will not remain.

01:53:55.060 --> 01:54:00.840
[Guest]: So even, you know, the Western interests which have thrived on those old establishments sooner

01:54:00.840 --> 01:54:04.200
[Guest]: than later will lose their hold.

01:54:04.200 --> 01:54:12.240
[Guest]: So there would be a genuine, I think, democratic upsurge to build a constructive opposition.

01:54:12.240 --> 01:54:14.320
[Guest]: And when I say this, I'm keeping my personal biases out.

01:54:14.320 --> 01:54:16.480
[Guest]: I'm not saying that this is right or the other is right.

01:54:16.480 --> 01:54:19.960
[Guest]: It could take any shape, any ideological inclination, etc.

01:54:19.960 --> 01:54:24.840
[Guest]: But there would be an effort to engage with the government.

01:54:24.840 --> 01:54:28.560
[Guest]: Not on what the today's opposition, not on terms on what the today's opposition thinks

01:54:28.560 --> 01:54:29.560
[Guest]: they should be.

01:54:29.560 --> 01:54:33.560
[Guest]: So there would be a large, because the kind of a young country we are, and the kind of

01:54:33.560 --> 01:54:39.080
[Guest]: problems our young generation faces, essentially jobs, employment, etc.

01:54:39.080 --> 01:54:42.240
[Guest]: Even people like us, professionally white collared otherwise, there's absolutely no

01:54:42.240 --> 01:54:43.240
[Guest]: job security.

01:54:43.240 --> 01:54:46.480
[Guest]: Now, India is a country where you have absolutely no social security, you know, you might be

01:54:46.480 --> 01:54:48.320
[Guest]: rich enough, you might have a medical insurance.

01:54:48.320 --> 01:54:52.080
[Guest]: But if you encounter serious illness, there's a lot of problem.

01:54:52.080 --> 01:54:57.360
[Guest]: So there has to be some sort of occupational solidarity among the young, at least, which

01:54:57.360 --> 01:55:02.200
[Guest]: will hopefully give a progressive tilt, you know, in terms of at least the economic policy

01:55:02.200 --> 01:55:03.200
[Guest]: of it.

01:55:03.200 --> 01:55:06.560
[Guest]: It has to be more egalitarian, we have to take care of development should not just be

01:55:06.560 --> 01:55:11.520
[Guest]: more roads and more flyovers and more airports, but it has to, it will have to hopefully take

01:55:11.520 --> 01:55:15.040
[Guest]: into account health and education is something which has not been done till now.

01:55:15.040 --> 01:55:18.760
[Amit Varma]: But that I think, you know, is the best case scenario we should all be hoping for.

01:55:18.760 --> 01:55:20.680
[Amit Varma]: On that hopeful note, thanks so much for coming on the show.

01:55:20.680 --> 01:55:22.480
[Amit Varma]: I learned a lot from talking to you today.

01:55:22.480 --> 01:55:26.520
[Amit Varma]: And I think it's a saving grace of our democracy that we have journalists like you around.

